{"title_page": "Siobhan McDonald", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish artist}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Siobh\u00e1n McDonald\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = Siobhan McDonald bio pic.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date       = \n| birth_place      = [[New York City]]\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = Irish\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = [[Limerick School of Art and Design]]\n| known_for        = Crystalline: Hidden Monuments\n| notable_works    = \n| style            = \n| home_town        = \n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n| partner          = \n| awards           = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) -->\n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = {{URL|http://www.siobhanmcdonald.com}}\n| module           = \n}}\n \n'''Siobh\u00e1n McDonald''' is an Irish artist based in [[Dublin, Ireland]] known for her recent artwork which is centered around climate change.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nMcDonald was born in [[New York City|New York]] of [[Northern Ireland]] parents from [[County Monaghan]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dillon |first1=Cathy |title=Siobh\u00e1n McDonald: the art of scientific exploration |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/art-and-design/siobh%C3%A1n-mcdonald-the-art-of-scientific-exploration-1.2147180 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref> but was raised in [[Ireland]] as her family moved back to [[Monaghan]], Ireland when she was two. As a child, McDonald was fascinated by geology and collected rocks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ahlstrom |first1=Dick |title=Layer by layer: how Siobh\u00e1n McDonald paints like a geologist |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/layer-by-layer-how-siobh%C3%A1n-mcdonald-paints-like-a-geologist-1.1820753 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref> McDonald holds a bachelor's degree in Art and Design from [[Ulster University]] and [[Master of Fine Arts|Masters in Visual Arts Practices]] from [[D\u00fan Laoghaire Institute of Art, Design and Technology]] in 2011.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news |last1=O\u2019Sullivan |first1=John |title=Her crystalline mine |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/her-crystalline-mine-b5nrgfp8c |work=[[The Times]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Visual Artists \u2013 Design {{!}} Previous Residents {{!}} Artists in Residence |url=https://www.centreculturelirlandais.com/en/residencies/artistes-en-residence/previous-residents?c=16 |publisher=[[Irish College in Paris]]}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |title=TEDxUCD {{!}} TED |url=https://www.ted.com/tedx/events/22942 |website=www.ted.com}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nMcDonald is the artist in residence in the School of Natural Sciences at Trinity College Dublin.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |last1=Leach |first1=Crist\u00edn |title=Artist Siobhan McDonald on geology, time and the Anthropocene |url=https://www.rte.ie/culture/2019/0129/1026276-artist-siobhan-mcdonald-on-geology-time-and-the-anthropocene/ |publisher=[[RT\u00c9.ie]] |language=en |date=5 February 2019}}</ref> She had several shows and often uses various materials like Gold, Cooper and Charcoal to paint on paper, board and canvas.<ref name=\"The Irish Times\">{{cite news |last1=McDonald |first1=Siobhan |title=Science meets art as Solar Orbiter embarks on its journey to the sun |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/science-meets-art-as-solar-orbiter-embarks-on-its-journey-to-the-sun-1.4195267 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Siobh\u00e1n McDonald - Artist, Fine Art Prices, Auction Records for Siobh\u00e1n McDonald |url=https://www.askart.com/artist/Siobhan_McDonald/11177710/Siobhan_McDonald.aspx |website=www.askart.com}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> Her work influenced by her interest in the natural world as she experimented with using a mixed palette of plaster, pigments, beeswax as well as traditional oil paints to create works that have a deep connection to nature.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2015, McDonald undertook an expedition to the Arctic Circle which was a pivotal point in her career moving to create larger installations and more imaginative and varied pieces of sculpture and video alongside her paintings. She collaborates on an ongoing basis with scientists and geologists as part of her work, bridging the gap between art and science.<ref>{{cite news |title=My Arctic Voyage of Self Discovery |url=https://thegloss.ie/arctic-role/ |work=The Gloss Magazine |date=5 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Carrington |first1=Damian |title=The Anthropocene epoch: scientists declare dawn of human-influenced age |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/aug/29/declare-anthropocene-epoch-experts-urge-geological-congress-human-impact-earth |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=29 August 2016}}</ref>\nIn 2019, McDonald traveled on another expedition to Catania with three scientists from TCD to study Mount Etna's pulsing, volatile terrain in the hope to discover the volcano's chemical make-up.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rainsford |first1=Sue |title=Ash to art: Can Mount Etna\u2019s eruptions tackle carbon emissions? |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/ash-to-art-can-mount-etna-s-eruptions-tackle-carbon-emissions-1.3760154 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref>\nIn December 2019, McDonald's work was exhibited in the \"Datami\" exhibition in BOZAR, [[Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels]].<ref name=\"The Irish Times\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Datami |url=https://www.bozar.be/en/activities/160618-datami |website=[[Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels]] |language=en}}</ref> McDonald's work was exhibited in Ireland and internationally and known in many private collections.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eye of the Storm \u2013 exhibition by Siobhan McDonald \u2013 DIAS |url=https://www.dias.ie/2012/04/30/eye-of-the-storm-exhibition-by-siobhan-mcdonald/ |publisher=[[Dublin Institute for Advanced Studies]]}}</ref>\nHer most recent work, Hidden Monuments was exhibited in the [[Limerick City Gallery of Art]] from February to March 2019.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |last1=Art |first1=Limerick City Gallery of |title=Siobhan McDonald, Crystalline: Hidden Monuments |url=http://gallery.limerick.ie/LCGAExhibitions/LCGAExhibitionsArchive/2019Exhibitions/SiobhanMcDonaldCrystallineHiddenMonuments.html |website=limerick.ie |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Crystalline: Hidden Monuments {{!}} Siobhan McDonald at Limerick City Gallery of Art |url=https://visualartists.ie/events/crystalline-hidden-monuments-siobhan-mcdonald-at-limerick-city-gallery-of-art/ |publisher=[[Visual Artists Ireland]] |date=1 February 2019}}</ref> Her practice in recent times has been focused on art intersecting with science on the theme of climate change.<ref>{{cite news |title=Breathe the pressure |url=https://www.businesspost.ie/more-life-arts/breathe-the-pressure-2710c8f9 |work=[[Business Post]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Siobhan McDonald\u2019s chance encounters with a changing world |url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/siobhan-mcdonalds-chance-encounters-changing-world/ |publisher=[[Apollo (magazine)]] |date=9 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nMcDonald was chosen to be the artist-in-residence for Climate Whirl arts program at the University of Helsinki in 2020.  She was the selected as the sole artist from 168 applications by a jury composed by [[:fi:Jaana B\u00e4ck|Jaana B\u00e4ck]], professor in Forest-Atmosphere Interactions (INAR, University of Helsinki), [[:fi:Timo Vesala|Timo Vesala]], professor in Meteorology (INAR, University of Helsinki), Henna Paunu, chief curator at EMMA (Espoo Museum for Modern Art), Paula Toppila executive director at IHME Helsinki and Ulla Taipale, curator of Climate Whirl.<ref>http://climatewhirl.fi/en/news Climate Whirl artist-in-residence 2020 is selected</ref>\n\n== Awards and accolades ==\n* 2020 - Artist in Residence, Climate Whirl arts program, 2020, University of Helsinki<ref name=\":2\" />\n* 2017 \u2013 The Trinity Creative Award, [[Trinity College Dublin]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Trinity Creative - FUTURE BREATH |url=https://www.tcd.ie/trinity-creative/challenge/2017/siobhan-mc-donald.php |publisher=[[Trinity College Dublin]]}}</ref>\n* 2017 \u2013 [[Bursary|Bursary Award]] by Arts Council Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |last1=webmaster |first1=Arts Council |title=Who we funded |url=http://www.artscouncil.ie/funding-decisions/?&Fund=Bursary%20award&Year=2017 |publisher=[[Arts Council (Ireland)]] |date=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n* 2017 \u2013 Residency at [[Centre Culturel Irlandais]], Paris.<ref name=\":2\" />\n* 2016  \u2013 BAI Sound and Vision, [[RT\u00c9 lyric fm|RT\u00c9 Lyric FM]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Lyric Feature Preview: An artist in the Arctic Circle |url=https://www.rte.ie/culture/2016/1005/821628-lyric-feature-preview/ |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |language=en |date=5 October 2016}}</ref>\n* Culture Ireland Award: Imagining Ireland in the UK.<ref>{{cite web |title=When Plants Remember - Crystalline |url=https://www.cultureireland.ie/GB18/event/when-plants-remember-crystalline |publisher=[[Culture Ireland]]}}</ref>\n\n== Solo Exhibitions ==\n*''Monuments for the future'', [[Limerick City Gallery of Art]], Ireland.<ref name=\":3\" />\n*''When plants remember'', The Henry Fox Talbot Museum, UK.<ref>{{cite web |title=Art at Lacock |url=https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/lacock-abbey-fox-talbot-museum-and-village/lists/art-and-installations-at-lacock-abbey |publisher=[[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty]] |language=en}}</ref>\n*''Crystalline'', [[Highlanes Gallery]], Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |title=Highlanes Gallery - Siobhan McDonald \u2013 A Change in the Signal \u2013 Crystalline, until Nov 25th |url=http://www.highlanes.ie/Activity.aspx?ActivityID=3330 |website=www.highlanes.ie}}</ref>\n*''Crystalline'', Centre Culturel Irlandais, Paris.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casassus |first1=Barbara |title=Arctic expeditions and stars collide to create 'quietly powerful' show |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2017/mar/17/crystalline-doomed-arctic-expeditions-and-stars-collide-to-create-quietly-powerful-show |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n*''Eye of the Storm'', The Galway Arts Centre.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Courtney |first1=Kevin |title=Volcanic art: \u2018Iceland is like a blank canvas\u2019 |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/volcanic-art-iceland-is-like-a-blank-canvas-1.1508369 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref>\n*''Disappearing Worlds''''',''' [[Taylor Galleries]], Dublin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.taylorgalleries.ie/Siobhan-McDonald-Crystalline-Disappearing-Worlds|title=Siobh\u00e1n McDonald - Crystalline: Disappearing Worlds - Taylor Galleries|website=www.taylorgalleries.ie|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.siobhanmcdonald.com/ Official Website]\n\n[[Category:Alumni of the Limerick School of Art and Design]]\n[[Category:Irish artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{short description|Irish artist}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Siobh\u00e1n McDonald\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = Siobhan McDonald bio pic.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date       = \n| birth_place      = [[New York City]]\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = Irish\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = [[Limerick School of Art and Design]]\n| known_for        = Crystalline: Hidden Monuments\n| notable_works    = \n| style            = \n| home_town        = \n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n| partner          = \n| awards           = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) -->\n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = {{URL|http://www.siobhanmcdonald.com}}\n| module           = \n}}\n \n'''Siobh\u00e1n McDonald''' is an Irish artist based in [[Dublin, Ireland]] known for her recent artwork which is centered around climate change.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nMcDonald was born in [[New York City|New York]] of [[Northern Ireland]] parents from [[County Monaghan]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dillon |first1=Cathy |title=Siobh\u00e1n McDonald: the art of scientific exploration |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/art-and-design/siobh%C3%A1n-mcdonald-the-art-of-scientific-exploration-1.2147180 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref> but was raised in [[Ireland]] as her family moved back to [[Monaghan]], Ireland when she was two. As a child, McDonald was fascinated by geology and collected rocks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ahlstrom |first1=Dick |title=Layer by layer: how Siobh\u00e1n McDonald paints like a geologist |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/layer-by-layer-how-siobh%C3%A1n-mcdonald-paints-like-a-geologist-1.1820753 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref> McDonald holds a bachelor's degree in Art and Design from [[Ulster University]] and [[Master of Fine Arts|Masters in Visual Arts Practices]] from [[D\u00fan Laoghaire Institute of Art, Design and Technology]] in 2011.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news |last1=O\u2019Sullivan |first1=John |title=Her crystalline mine |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/her-crystalline-mine-b5nrgfp8c |work=[[The Times]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Visual Artists \u2013 Design {{!}} Previous Residents {{!}} Artists in Residence |url=https://www.centreculturelirlandais.com/en/residencies/artistes-en-residence/previous-residents?c=16 |publisher=[[Irish College in Paris]]}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |title=TEDxUCD {{!}} TED |url=https://www.ted.com/tedx/events/22942 |website=www.ted.com}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nMcDonald is the artist in residence in the School of Natural Sciences at Trinity College Dublin.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |last1=Leach |first1=Crist\u00edn |title=Artist Siobhan McDonald on geology, time and the Anthropocene |url=https://www.rte.ie/culture/2019/0129/1026276-artist-siobhan-mcdonald-on-geology-time-and-the-anthropocene/ |publisher=[[RT\u00c9.ie]] |language=en |date=5 February 2019}}</ref> She had several shows and often uses various materials like Gold, Cooper and Charcoal to paint on paper, board and canvas.<ref name=\"The Irish Times\">{{cite news |last1=McDonald |first1=Siobhan |title=Science meets art as Solar Orbiter embarks on its journey to the sun |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/science-meets-art-as-solar-orbiter-embarks-on-its-journey-to-the-sun-1.4195267 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Siobh\u00e1n McDonald - Artist, Fine Art Prices, Auction Records for Siobh\u00e1n McDonald |url=https://www.askart.com/artist/Siobhan_McDonald/11177710/Siobhan_McDonald.aspx |website=www.askart.com}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> Her work influenced by her interest in the natural world as she experimented with using a mixed palette of plaster, pigments, beeswax as well as traditional oil paints to create works that have a deep connection to nature.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2015, McDonald undertook an expedition to the Arctic Circle which was a pivotal point in her career moving to create larger installations and more imaginative and varied pieces of sculpture and video alongside her paintings. She collaborates on an ongoing basis with scientists and geologists as part of her work, bridging the gap between art and science.<ref>{{cite news |title=My Arctic Voyage of Self Discovery |url=https://thegloss.ie/arctic-role/ |work=The Gloss Magazine |date=5 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Carrington |first1=Damian |title=The Anthropocene epoch: scientists declare dawn of human-influenced age |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/aug/29/declare-anthropocene-epoch-experts-urge-geological-congress-human-impact-earth |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=29 August 2016}}</ref>\nIn 2019, McDonald traveled on another expedition to Catania with three scientists from TCD to study Mount Etna's pulsing, volatile terrain in the hope to discover the volcano's chemical make-up.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rainsford |first1=Sue |title=Ash to art: Can Mount Etna\u2019s eruptions tackle carbon emissions? |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/ash-to-art-can-mount-etna-s-eruptions-tackle-carbon-emissions-1.3760154 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref>\nIn December 2019, McDonald's work was exhibited in the \"Datami\" exhibition in BOZAR, [[Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels]].<ref name=\"The Irish Times\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Datami |url=https://www.bozar.be/en/activities/160618-datami |website=[[Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels]] |language=en}}</ref> McDonald's work was exhibited in Ireland and internationally and known in many private collections.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eye of the Storm \u2013 exhibition by Siobhan McDonald \u2013 DIAS |url=https://www.dias.ie/2012/04/30/eye-of-the-storm-exhibition-by-siobhan-mcdonald/ |publisher=[[Dublin Institute for Advanced Studies]]}}</ref>\nHer most recent work, Hidden Monuments was exhibited in the [[Limerick City Gallery of Art]] from February to March 2019.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |last1=Art |first1=Limerick City Gallery of |title=Siobhan McDonald, Crystalline: Hidden Monuments |url=http://gallery.limerick.ie/LCGAExhibitions/LCGAExhibitionsArchive/2019Exhibitions/SiobhanMcDonaldCrystallineHiddenMonuments.html |website=limerick.ie |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Crystalline: Hidden Monuments {{!}} Siobhan McDonald at Limerick City Gallery of Art |url=https://visualartists.ie/events/crystalline-hidden-monuments-siobhan-mcdonald-at-limerick-city-gallery-of-art/ |publisher=[[Visual Artists Ireland]] |date=1 February 2019}}</ref> Her practice in recent times has been focused on art intersecting with science on the theme of climate change.<ref>{{cite news |title=Breathe the pressure |url=https://www.businesspost.ie/more-life-arts/breathe-the-pressure-2710c8f9 |work=[[Business Post]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Siobhan McDonald\u2019s chance encounters with a changing world |url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/siobhan-mcdonalds-chance-encounters-changing-world/ |publisher=[[Apollo (magazine)]] |date=9 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nMcDonald was chosen to be the artist-in-residence for Climate Whirl arts program at the University of Helsinki in 2020.  She was the selected as the sole artist from 168 applications by a jury composed by [[:fi:Jaana B\u00e4ck|Jaana B\u00e4ck]], professor in Forest-Atmosphere Interactions (INAR, University of Helsinki), [[:fi:Timo Vesala|Timo Vesala]], professor in Meteorology (INAR, University of Helsinki), Henna Paunu, chief curator at EMMA (Espoo Museum for Modern Art), Paula Toppila executive director at IHME Helsinki and Ulla Taipale, curator of Climate Whirl.<ref>http://climatewhirl.fi/en/news Climate Whirl artist-in-residence 2020 is selected</ref>\n\n== Awards and accolades ==\n* 2020 - Artist in Residence, Climate Whirl arts program, 2020, University of Helsinki<ref name=\":2\" />\n* 2017 \u2013 The Trinity Creative Award, [[Trinity College Dublin]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Trinity Creative - FUTURE BREATH |url=https://www.tcd.ie/trinity-creative/challenge/2017/siobhan-mc-donald.php |publisher=[[Trinity College Dublin]]}}</ref>\n* 2017 \u2013 [[Bursary|Bursary Award]] by Arts Council Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |last1=webmaster |first1=Arts Council |title=Who we funded |url=http://www.artscouncil.ie/funding-decisions/?&Fund=Bursary%20award&Year=2017 |publisher=[[Arts Council (Ireland)]] |date=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n* 2017 \u2013 Residency at [[Centre Culturel Irlandais]], Paris.<ref name=\":2\" />\n* 2016  \u2013 BAI Sound and Vision, [[RT\u00c9 lyric fm|RT\u00c9 Lyric FM]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Lyric Feature Preview: An artist in the Arctic Circle |url=https://www.rte.ie/culture/2016/1005/821628-lyric-feature-preview/ |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |language=en |date=5 October 2016}}</ref>\n* Culture Ireland Award: Imagining Ireland in the UK.<ref>{{cite web |title=When Plants Remember - Crystalline |url=https://www.cultureireland.ie/GB18/event/when-plants-remember-crystalline |publisher=[[Culture Ireland]]}}</ref>\n\n== Solo Exhibitions ==\n*''Monuments for the future'', [[Limerick City Gallery of Art]], Ireland.<ref name=\":3\" />\n*''When plants remember'', The Henry Fox Talbot Museum, UK.<ref>{{cite web |title=Art at Lacock |url=https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/lacock-abbey-fox-talbot-museum-and-village/lists/art-and-installations-at-lacock-abbey |publisher=[[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty]] |language=en}}</ref>\n*''Crystalline'', [[Highlanes Gallery]], Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |title=Highlanes Gallery - Siobhan McDonald \u2013 A Change in the Signal \u2013 Crystalline, until Nov 25th |url=http://www.highlanes.ie/Activity.aspx?ActivityID=3330 |website=www.highlanes.ie}}</ref>\n*''Crystalline'', Centre Culturel Irlandais, Paris.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casassus |first1=Barbara |title=Arctic expeditions and stars collide to create 'quietly powerful' show |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2017/mar/17/crystalline-doomed-arctic-expeditions-and-stars-collide-to-create-quietly-powerful-show |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n*''Eye of the Storm'', The Galway Arts Centre.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Courtney |first1=Kevin |title=Volcanic art: \u2018Iceland is like a blank canvas\u2019 |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/volcanic-art-iceland-is-like-a-blank-canvas-1.1508369 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref>\n*''Disappearing Worlds''''',''' [[Taylor Galleries]], Dublin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.taylorgalleries.ie/Siobhan-McDonald-Crystalline-Disappearing-Worlds|title=Siobh\u00e1n McDonald - Crystalline: Disappearing Worlds - Taylor Galleries|website=www.taylorgalleries.ie|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.siobhanmcdonald.com/ Official Website]\n\n[[Category:Alumni of the Limerick School of Art and Design]]\n[[Category:Irish artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Keitholoughlin", "label": "safe", "comment": "deorphaned as article has 3 inbound wikipedia links.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siobhan_McDonald"}
{"title_page": "Tora! Tora! Tora!", "text_new": "{{other uses|Tora Tora Tora (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Japanese-American war film about the attack on Pearl Harbor}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Tora! Tora! Tora!\n| image          = ToraToraTora1970.png\n| caption        = Original movie poster\n| director       = '''American sequences'''<br>[[Richard Fleischer]]<br>'''Japanese sequences'''<br>[[Toshio Masuda (director)|Toshio Masuda]]<br>[[Kinji Fukasaku]]\n| producer       = [[Elmo Williams]]<br>Richard Fleischer <small>(uncredited)\n| screenplay     = '''American sequences'''<br>Larry Forrester<br>'''Japanese sequences'''<br>[[Hideo Oguni]]<br>[[Ry\u016bz\u014d Kikushima]]<br>[[Akira Kurosawa]] <small>(uncredited)\n| based on       = {{based on|''Tora! Tora! Tora!''<br>1969 book|[[Gordon W. Prange]]<br>and ''The Broken Seal'' by<br>[[Ladislas Farago]]}}\n| starring       = [[Martin Balsam]]<br>[[S\u014d Yamamura]]<br>[[Joseph Cotten]]<br>[[Tatsuya Mihashi]]<br>[[E. G. Marshall]]<br>[[James Whitmore]]<br>[[Takahiro Tamura]]<br>[[Eijir\u014d T\u014dno]]<br>[[Jason Robards]]\n| music          = [[Jerry Goldsmith]]\n| cinematography = '''American sequences'''<br>[[Charles F. Wheeler]]<br>'''Japanese sequences'''<br>Shinsaku Himeda<br>Masamichi Satoh<br>Osamu Furuya\n| editing        = [[James E. Newcom]]<br>[[Pembroke J. Herring]]<br>Inoue Chikaya\n| distributor    = [[20th Century Fox]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1970|09|23}}\n| runtime        = 144 minutes\n| country        = Japan<br />United States\n| language       = English<br>Japanese\n| budget         = $25.5 million<!--$25,485,000--><ref name=\"Parish p. 411\"/><ref>Solomon, Aubrey. ''Twentieth Century Fox: A Corporate and Financial History (The Scarecrow Filmmakers Series)''. Lanham, Maryland: Scarecrow Press, 1989. {{ISBN|978-0-8108-4244-1}}. p256</ref>\n| gross          = $29.5 million <!--$29,548,291-->{{small|(domestic)}}<ref>[http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/1970/00260.php \"Box Office Information for Tora! Tora! Tora!\"] ''[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]].'' Retrieved: January 9, 2012.</ref>\n}}\n'''''Tora! Tora! Tora!''''' ({{lang-ja|\u30c8\u30e9\u30fb\u30c8\u30e9\u30fb\u30c8\u30e9\uff01}}) is a 1970 [[epic film|epic]] [[war film]] that dramatizes the [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] [[attack on Pearl Harbor]] in 1941. The film was produced by [[Elmo Williams]] and directed by [[Richard Fleischer]]<!--The Japanese segments form a significant portion of the film:-->, [[Toshio Masuda (director)|Toshio Masuda]] and [[Kinji Fukasaku]], and stars an [[ensemble cast]] including [[Martin Balsam]], [[Joseph Cotten]], [[S\u014d Yamamura]], [[E. G. Marshall]], [[James Whitmore]], [[Tatsuya Mihashi]], [[Takahiro Tamura]], [[Wesley Addy]], and [[Jason Robards]]. It was Masuda and Fukasaku's first English-language film, and first non-Japanese film.\n\nThe ''tora'' of the title is the two-syllable [[Japanese language|Japanese]] [[Code name|codeword]] used to indicate that complete surprise had been achieved. Japanese being a language with many [[homophone]]s, it is a coincidence that ''tora'' also means \"tiger\" ({{lang|ja|\u864e}}).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://iknow.jp/courses/618828|title=Japanese Phonology: Homophones from Core Lists (complete) \u2013 iKnow!|last=http://corp.dmm.com/|first=\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793eDMM.com -|website=iknow.jp|language=en|access-date=2017-11-22}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|limit=2}}\n\n==Plot==\nIn August 1939, the United States imposes a trade embargo on a belligerent Japan, severely limiting raw materials. Influential [[Imperial Japanese Army|army]] figures and politicians push through an  [[Tripartite Pact| alliance with Germany and Italy]] in September 1940 and prepare for war. The newly appointed Commander-in-Chief of the [[Japanese Combined Fleet|Combined Fleet]], [[Isoroku Yamamoto|Admiral Isoroku Yamamoto]], reluctantly plans a pre-emptive strike on the U.S. Pacific Fleet anchored at [[Pearl Harbor]], believing that Japan's best hope of controlling the [[Pacific Ocean]] is to quickly annihilate the American fleet. Air Staff Officer [[Minoru Genda]] is chosen to mastermind the operation while his old Naval Academy classmate [[Mitsuo Fuchida]] is selected to lead the attack.\n\nMeanwhile, in Washington, U.S. military intelligence has broken the Japanese ''[[Purple (cipher machine)|Purple Code]]'', allowing them to intercept secret Japanese radio transmissions indicating increased Japanese naval activity. Monitoring the transmissions are U.S. Army Col. Bratton and U.S. Navy Lt. Commander Kramer. At Pearl Harbor itself, Admiral Kimmel and General Short do their best to increase defensive naval and air patrols around Hawaii which could provide early warning of enemy presence. Short recommends concentrating aircraft at the base on the runways to avoid sabotage by enemy agents in Hawaii.\n\nSeveral months pass while diplomatic tensions escalate. As the Japanese ambassador to Washington continues negotiations to stall for time, the large Japanese fleet sorties into the Pacific. On the day of the attack, Bratton and Kramer learn from intercepts that the Japanese plan a series of 14 radio messages from Tokyo to the Japanese embassy in Washington. They are also directed to destroy their code machines after receiving the final message. Deducing the Japanese intention to launch a surprise attack immediately after the messages are delivered, Bratton tries warning his superiors of his suspicions but encounters several obstacles: Chief of Naval Operations [[Harold Rainsford Stark|Harold R. Stark]] is indecisive over notifying Hawaii without first alerting the President while Army Chief of Staff General [[George Marshall]]'s order that Pearl Harbor be alerted of an impending attack is stymied by poor atmospherics that prevent radio transmission and by bungling when a warning sent by telegram is not marked urgent. At dawn on December 7, the Japanese fleet launches its aircraft. Their approach to Hawaii is detected by two radar operators but their concerns are dismissed by the duty officer. The Japanese thus achieve surprise and a joyous commander Fuchida sends the code to begin the attack: \"Tora! Tora! Tora!\"\n\nThe damage to the naval base is catastrophic and casualties are severe. Seven battleships are either sunk or heavily damaged. General Short's anti-sabotage precautions prove a disastrous mistake that allows the Japanese aerial forces to destroy aircraft on the ground easily. Hours after the attack ends, General Short and Admiral Kimmel receive Marshall's telegram warning of impending danger. In Washington, [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] [[Cordell Hull]] is stunned to learn of the attack and urgently requests confirmation before receiving the Japanese ambassador. The message that was transmitted to the Japanese embassy in 14 parts \u2013 a declaration of war \u2013 was meant to be delivered to the Americans at 1:00 pm in Washington, 30 minutes before the attack. However, it was not decoded and transcribed in time, meaning the attack started while the two nations were technically still at peace. The distraught [[Kichisabur\u014d Nomura|Japanese ambassador]], helpless to explain the late ultimatum and unaware of the ongoing attack, is bluntly rebuffed by a despondent Hull.\n\nBack in the Pacific, the Japanese fleet commander, Vice-Admiral [[Ch\u016bichi Nagumo]], refuses to launch a scheduled third wave of aircraft for fear of exposing his force to U.S. submarines. Aboard his flagship, Admiral Yamamoto solemnly informs his staff that their primary target \u2013 the American aircraft carriers \u2013 were not at Pearl Harbor, having departed days previously to search for Japanese vessels. Lamenting that the declaration of war arrived after the attack began, Yamamoto notes that nothing would infuriate the U.S. more and ominously concludes: \"I fear all we have done is to awaken a sleeping giant and fill him with a terrible resolve.\"\n\n==Cast==\n=== Allies ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \"\n!Actor\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Martin Balsam]]\n|[[Admiral (United States)|Admiral]] [[Husband E. Kimmel]]\n|[[Commander-in-Chief]], [[U.S. Pacific Fleet]]\n|-\n|[[Joseph Cotten]]\n|Secretary [[Henry L. Stimson|Henry Stimson]]\n|U.S. [[United States Secretary of War|Secretary of War]]\n|-\n|[[E. G. Marshall]]\n|[[Lieutenant Colonel (United States)|Lt. Colonel]] [[Rufus S. Bratton]]\n|Chief, Far Eastern Section, Military Intelligence Division, [[United States Department of War|War Department]]\n|-\n|[[James Whitmore]]\n|[[Vice Admiral (United States)|Vice Admiral]] [[William Halsey Jr.]]\n|Commander, Aircraft Battle Force, U.S. Pacific Fleet\n|-\n|[[Jason Robards]]\n|[[Lieutenant General (United States)|General]] [[Walter Short]]\n|Commander-in-Chief, [[United States Army Pacific Command|U.S. Army Forces Hawaii]]\n|-\n|[[Wesley Addy]]\n|[[Lieutenant Commander (United States)|Lt. Commander]] Alwin Kramer\n|Cryptographer, [[OP-20-G]]\n|-\n|[[Frank Aletter]]\n|[[Lieutenant Commander (United States)|Lt. Commander]] Francis Thomas\n|Command Duty Officer, [[USS Nevada (BB-36)|USS ''Nevada'']]\n|-\n|[[Leon Ames (actor)|Leon Ames]]\n|Secretary [[Frank Knox]]\n|U.S. [[United States Secretary of the Navy|Secretary of the Navy]]\n|-\n|[[Richard Anderson]]\n|[[Captain (United States O-6)|Captain]] John Earle\n|Chief of Staff, [[14th Naval District]]\n|-\n|[[Keith Andes]]\n|[[General (United States)|General]] [[George Marshall|George C. Marshall]]\n|[[Chief of Staff of the U.S. Army]]\n|-\n|[[Edward Andrews]]\n|Admiral [[Harold Rainsford Stark]]\n|[[Chief of Naval Operations]]\n|-\n|[[Neville Brand]]\n|Lt. Harold Kaminski\n|Duty Officer, 14th Naval District\n|-\n|[[George Macready]]\n|Secretary [[Cordell Hull]]\n|[[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]]\n|-\n|[[Norman Alden]]\n|[[Major (United States)|Major]] [[Truman H. Landon|Truman Landon]]\n|Commanding Officer, [[38th Reconnaissance Squadron]]