y are due to travel history or close contact.<ref>{{cite web |title=Newsroom : News: Health |url=https://news.ontario.ca/mohltc/en |website=news.ontario.ca |access-date=March 10, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310003242/https://news.ontario.ca/mohltc/en |archive-date=March 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Ministry of Health (Ontario)|Ontario Minister of Health and Long-Term Care]], [[Christine Elliott]], has been overseeing the emergency plan for the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.toronto.com/news-story/9881027-ontario-government-has-a-coronavirus-outbreak-plan-but-won-t-reveal-details/|title=Ontario government has a coronavirus outbreak plan but won't reveal details|last=Ferguson|first=Rob|date=2020-03-09|website=Toronto.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-03-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312174116/https://www.toronto.com/news-story/9881027-ontario-government-has-a-coronavirus-outbreak-plan-but-won-t-reveal-details/|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, the Government of Ontario announced publicly funded schools would be closed for an additional two weeks after [[Spring break|March Break]] until April 5.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-government-closing-schools-1.5495736|title=Ontario to shut down publicly funded schools for 2 weeks after March Break over COVID-19 concerns|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318155003/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-government-closing-schools-1.5495736|archive-date=March 18, 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, The Ontario Superior Court of Justice announced a suspension of most criminal matters, including trials until the end of May.<ref>{{cite web |title=Notice to Accused Persons, Profession, Crown, Public Prosecution Service of Canada, Correctional Institutions, Witnesses, Jurors, The Public and The Media Regarding Criminal Operations |url=https://www.ontariocourts.ca/scj/covid-19-suspension-crim/ |website=www.ontariocourts.ca |publisher=Superior Court of Justice}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Ontario Premier [[Doug Ford]] declared a province-wide [[state of emergency]].<ref name=\"emergency\"/> This included prohibition of all public events of over 50 people (later reduced to 5 people on March 28), closure of bars and restaurants (with the exception that restaurants may continue to provide takeout and delivery services) as well as libraries, theatres, cinemas, private schools (in addition to publicly-funded schools which were already been ordered closed from March 14 until further notice) and daycares.<ref name=\"death\"/><ref name=\"gatheringban5\" /> The following day, a state of emergency was also declared in [[Regional Municipality of Peel|Peel Region]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://peelregion.ca/news/archiveitem.asp?year=2020&month=2&day=18&file=2020218.xml|title=Region of Peel declares Emergency to protect health and safety of residents and staff|publisher=peelregion.ca|date=March 18, 2020|access-date=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320180506/https://peelregion.ca/news/archiveitem.asp?year=2020&month=2&day=18&file=2020218.xml|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Simcoe County]] by Warden George Cornell.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.simcoe.ca/CorporateCommunications/Pages/county-of-simcoe-declares-covid-19-emergency-20-3-18.aspx|title=County of Simcoe declares COVID-19 emergency|publisher=simcoe.ca|date=March 18, 2020|access-date=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324191008/https://www.simcoe.ca/CorporateCommunications/Pages/county-of-simcoe-declares-covid-19-emergency-20-3-18.aspx|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20 further measures were announced including waiving the three months waiting period for health care coverage,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.ontario.ca/mohltc/en/2020/03/ontario-expands-coverage-for-care.html|title=Ontario Expands Coverage for Care|website=news.ontario.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322200921/https://news.ontario.ca/mohltc/en/2020/03/ontario-expands-coverage-for-care.html|archive-date=March 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> the launch of an e-learning portal<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.ontario.ca/opo/en/2020/03/ontario-helping-students-learn-from-the-safety-of-their-own-home.html|title=Ontario Helping Students Learn from the Safety of Their Own Home|website=news.ontario.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322200922/https://news.ontario.ca/opo/en/2020/03/ontario-helping-students-learn-from-the-safety-of-their-own-home.html|archive-date=March 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and extended privileges for hospitals to re-deploy staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.ontario.ca/mohltc/en/2020/03/ontario-takes-extraordinary-steps-to-ensure-health-care-resources-are-available-to-contain-covid-19.html|title=Ontario Takes Extraordinary Steps to Ensure Health Care Resources are Available to Contain COVID-19|website=news.ontario.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322200924/https://news.ontario.ca/mohltc/en/2020/03/ontario-takes-extraordinary-steps-to-ensure-health-care-resources-are-available-to-contain-covid-19.html|archive-date=March 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Ford announced that all \"non-essential\" businesses be ordered closed starting 11:59&nbsp;p.m. on March 24. Ford also stated that schools would remain closed past the original April 6 opening date and until further notice.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ontario-schools-will-not-reopen-april-6-premier-says-1.4864551| title = Ontario schools will not reopen April 6, premier says| date = March 23, 2020| access-date = March 23, 2020| language = en| trans-title = | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200323185123/https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ontario-schools-will-not-reopen-april-6-premier-says-1.4864551| archive-date = March 23, 2020| url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = https://nationalpost.com/news/covid-19-ontario-and-quebec-order-non-essential-businesses-closed-after-spike-in-coronavirus-totals| title = COVID-19: Ontario and Quebec order non-essential businesses closed after spike in coronavirus totals| date = March 23, 2020| access-date = March 23, 2020| language = en| trans-title = }}</ref> A list of 74 \"essential\" businesses was published later in the day on March 23.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ford-says-list-of-essential-businesses-amid-covid-19-pandemic-is-adjustable-1.4865528|title=Ford says list of essential businesses amid COVID-19 pandemic is 'adjustable'|date=2020-03-24|website=CTV News Toronto|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325181806/https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ford-says-list-of-essential-businesses-amid-covid-19-pandemic-is-adjustable-1.4865528|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-list-essential-businesses-1.5507687|title=Ontario government releases list of essential workplaces that can remain open|last=|first=|date=2020-03-23|website=CBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325165046/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-list-essential-businesses-1.5507687|archive-date=March 25, 2020|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ontario-orders-all-non-essential-businesses-to-shut-down-1.4864492|title=Ontario orders all non-essential businesses to shut down|date=2020-03-23|website=CTV News Toronto|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325193928/https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ontario-orders-all-non-essential-businesses-to-shut-down-1.4864492|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The same day, a state of emergency was declared in Toronto by Mayor [[John Tory]],<ref>{{cite web| url = https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/toronto-declares-state-of-emergency-amid-covid-19-pandemic-1.4864679| title = Toronto declares state of emergency amid COVID-19 pandemic| date = March 23, 2020| access-date = March 23, 2020| language = en| trans-title = | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200323192730/https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/toronto-declares-state-of-emergency-amid-covid-19-pandemic-1.4864679| archive-date = March 23, 2020| url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet| user=JohnTory| number=1242165183465783306| author=John Tory| date=March 23, 2020| title=We are declaring a State of Emergency as part of the City's ongoing efforts to stop the spread of COVID-19 and to ensure the municipal government can continue to act and respond quickly to the pandemic and any other events that arise in the weeks ahead.}}</ref> in [[Regional Municipality of York|York Region]] by Chair Wayne Emmerson,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.york.ca/wps/portal/yorkhome/newsroom/mediarelease/yorkregionchairmanandceowayneemmersondeclaresstateofemergencyacrosstheregionalmunicipalityofyork/|title=York Region Chairman and CEO Wayne Emmerson declares state of emergency across The Regional Municipality of York|publisher=york.ca| date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> and in [[Regional Municipality of Halton|Halton Region]] by Chair Gary Carr.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.halton.ca/The-Region/News/2020/Regional-Chair-declares-state-of-emergency-in-resp|title=Regional Chair declares state of emergency in response to COVID-19|publisher=halton.ca|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324191011/https://www.halton.ca/The-Region/News/2020/Regional-Chair-declares-state-of-emergency-in-resp|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The following day, a state of emergency was also declared in [[Regional Municipality of Durham|Durham Region]] by Chair John Henry<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.durham.ca/modules/news/index.aspx?newsId=0237de13-9c0c-4eb6-9624-71d1607e3472|title=Durham Region declares state of emergency|publisher=durham.ca|date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> and in [[Kawartha Lakes]] by Mayor Andy Letham.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kawarthalakes.ca/en/news/covid-19-update-19-video-message-from-mayor-letham-on-declaration-of-state-of-emergency.aspx|title=COVID-19 Update 19 Video Message from Mayor Letham on Declaration of State of Emergency|publisher=kawarthalakes.ca|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324191008/https://www.kawarthalakes.ca/en/news/covid-19-update-19-video-message-from-mayor-letham-on-declaration-of-state-of-emergency.aspx|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, Ford and [[Ministry of Finance (Ontario)|Finance Minister]] [[Rod Phillips (politician)|Rod Phillips]] introduced a $17-billion response package that includes an influx of cash for the health sector, direct payments to parents and tax breaks for businesses.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/2020-fiscal-update-1.5510186|title=Ontario introduces $17B COVID-19 package; more than doubles deficit in fiscal update|publisher=cbc.ca|date=March 25, 2020|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326180709/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/2020-fiscal-update-1.5510186|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, a municipal state of emergency was declared in [[Kingston, Ontario|Kingston]] by Mayor [[Bryan Paterson]] due to two new cases of the virus announced by [[KFL&A Public Health]]. Three recent cases in [[Lennox and Addington County|the region]] had reported no prior close contact with known infected persons, causing health officials to conclude that community transmission is present in the region, and closures of several medical clinics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6736452/community-spread-of-covid-19-confirmed-city-of-kingston-declares-state-of-emergency/|title=Community spread of COVID-19 confirmed, Kingston region declares states of emergency|publisher=globalnews.ca|date=March 26, 2020|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326180149/https://globalnews.ca/news/6736452/community-spread-of-covid-19-confirmed-city-of-kingston-declares-state-of-emergency/|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, following California and British Columbia, takeout and delivery orders from restaurants can include alcoholic beverages as long as the order contains food items and is ordered between 9 a.m. and 11 p.m.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.agco.ca/bulletin/2020/info-bulletin-no-61-liquor-sales-licensees-may-now-sell-liquor-takeout-or-delivery|title=Info Bulletin No. 61: Liquor sales licensees may now sell liquor for takeout or delivery along with food &#124; Alcohol and Gaming Commission of Ontario|website=www.agco.ca|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327030841/https://www.agco.ca/bulletin/2020/info-bulletin-no-61-liquor-sales-licensees-may-now-sell-liquor-takeout-or-delivery|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27 at 2:00&nbsp;p.m. ET, [[Alert Ready]] was activated on all radio stations, television channels and providers, and [[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]] wireless networks in Ontario, to distribute a warning informing travellers returning to Ontario of the mandatory self-isolation requirements under federal law.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/coronavirus-alert-1.5512525|title=Ontario issuing emergency alert on COVID-19 to phones, radios and TVs|work=[[CBC News]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327185645/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/coronavirus-alert-1.5512525|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the anticipated increase in patients requiring critical care, the Ontario government announced on March 27 that over 3,000 ventilators are ready to be deployed in Ontario (compared to the current capacity of approximately 1,300 critical care beds with ventilators and 43 patients requiring critical care as of March 27).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6742260/coronavirus-ontario-hospitals-ventilators-covid-19/|title=Coronavirus: Up to 3,250 ventilators ready to be deployed in Ontario, officials say|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, the Ontario government extended the state of emergency through April 13, and also ordered the province-wide closure of all outdoor recreational amenities, including beaches, playgrounds and sports facilities (several Ontario municipalities including Toronto, had already ordered similar closures of their recreational amenities several days prior to the province-wide order).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6754560/coronavirus-ontario-outdoor-recreation-amenities-closure-order/|title=Coronavirus: Ontario government orders shutdown of all outdoor recreation amenities|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331122621/https://globalnews.ca/news/6754560/coronavirus-ontario-outdoor-recreation-amenities-closure-order/|archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On March 31, it was announced that the schools would remain closed until at least May 4.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-students-covid19-1.5516104|title=Ontario unveils details of learn-at-home program, students out of school until at least May 4|publisher=cbc.ca|date=March 31, 2020|access-date=April 1, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401034329/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-students-covid19-1.5516104|archive-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The same day, Mayor of Toronto John Tory announced that the city would cancel all city-led major events, festivals (including [[Pride Toronto|Toronto's Pride Parade]], which was scheduled to take place on June 28), conferences, permits and cultural programs until June 30. Tory clarified that this does not necessarily restrict professional sporting events, but they are still covered under provincial restrictions on public gatherings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6758350/coronavirus-toronto-cancels-events-pride-parade/|title=Coronavirus: City of Toronto cancels events through June 30, including Pride Parade|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401002824/https://globalnews.ca/news/6758350/coronavirus-toronto-cancels-events-pride-parade/|archive-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/id/28978500/toronto-pro-sports-teams-not-impacted-new-ban-official-says|title=Toronto official: Ban doesn't include pro teams|date=2020-03-31|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403224722/https://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/id/28978500/toronto-pro-sports-teams-not-impacted-new-ban-official-says|archive-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn April 3, it was announced the number of \"essential\" businesses would be reduced to 44 beginning 11:59 p.m. on April 4; this included the halting of most non-essential construction, including industrial construction, and residential construction that did not begin before April 4, but excluding \"critical\" infrastructure projects, as well as the closure of all cannabis stores.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/more-ontario-businesses-some-construction-sites-will-close-amid-covid-19-pandemic-1.4881216|title=More Ontario businesses, some construction sites will close amid COVID-19 pandemic|last=DeClerq|first=Katherine|date=2020-04-03|website=Toronto|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/cannabis-stores-in-ontario-no-longer-deemed-essential-will-close-this-weekend-1.4881547|title=Cannabis stores in Ontario no longer deemed essential, will close this weekend|last=Goodfield|first=Kayla|date=2020-04-03|website=Toronto|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6774918/coronavirus-ontario-workplace-construction-closures/|title=Coronavirus: Ontario orders further workplace closures, halt to many construction projects|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404032802/https://globalnews.ca/news/6774918/coronavirus-ontario-workplace-construction-closures/|archive-date=April 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThe same day (April 3), the government released extensive data modelling that claimed that public health measures in the province prevented an estimated 220,000 cases and 4,400 deaths up to that point. Between 3,000 and 15,000 deaths related to COVID-19 were predicted with the current public health measures over the course of the pandemic, compared to a total projected 100,000 deaths if no action were taken, and if further measures are taken, models showed projections as low as 12,500 additional cases and 200 additional deaths by the end of April.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://news.ontario.ca/opo/en/2020/04/ontario-provides-full-transparency-by-releasing-covid-19-modelling.html|title=Ontario Provides Full Transparency by Releasing COVID-19 Modelling|publisher=news.ontario.ca|date=April 3, 2020|access-date=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404110058/https://news.ontario.ca/opo/en/2020/04/ontario-provides-full-transparency-by-releasing-covid-19-modelling.html|archive-date=April 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The models projected that by April 30 there would be 80,000 cases and 1600 deaths under the current interventions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/how-ontario-s-covid-19-models-are-comparing-to-reality-1.4887178|title=How Ontario's COVID-19 models are comparing to reality|date=2020-04-07|website=Toronto|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> In addition, the government projected a peak use of ICU beds of 1200 beds by April 18 under their best-case scenario (with over 3000 ICU beds required under the worst-case scenario by April 30).<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nOn April 14 during an emergency session, the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario|Legislative Assembly]] voted to extend the provincial state of emergency through May 12.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/this-crisis-is-far-from-over-ontario-extends-state-of-emergency-until-may-12-1.4895050|title='This crisis is far from over': Ontario extends state of emergency until May 12|last=Goodfield|first=Kayla|date=2020-04-14|website=CTV News Toronto|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> Premier Ford also announced that public schools would not open on May 4 as previously planned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ontario-public-schools-will-not-reopen-on-may-4-premier-says-1.4895807|title=Ontario public schools will not reopen on May 4, premier says|date=2020-04-14|website=Toronto|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n\n===Initial response===\nRegional public health experts suggested that Ontario's initial incremental response \u2014 adding new voluntary measures piece by piece \u2014 had been ineffective. Businesses of all sizes remained open, and unnecessary social contacts continued. Describing Ontario's efforts to battle COVID-19 as piecemeal and ineffective, Dr. Shanker Nesathurai, who was one of Ontario's 34 regional medical officers of health, urged his colleagues to band together and use more powerful measures to contain the pandemic than provincial leaders had endorsed by the third week of March. In an email, Dr. Nesathurai, who worked for [[Haldimand-Norfolk|Haldimand Norfolk Health Unit]], wrote on March 19 that Ontario's response had undermined the province's attempt to contain the outbreak, as businesses remain open and travellers ignore advice to self-isolate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2020/03/20/leaked-email-reveals-ontario-regional-medical-officers-criticism-of-provincial-covid-19-strategy-as-cracks-emerge-in-front-line.html|title=Leaked email reveals Ontario regional medical officer\u2019s criticism of provincial COVID-19 strategy as cracks emerge in front line|date=March 20, 2020|website=thestar.com}}</ref> \n\n===Testing issues===\nWhile Ontario initially did not have enough testing centres in Ontario in March to meet demand, that issue was resolved, before there were not enough labs to process the resultant tests, and later, not enough supplies of [[reagent]] to complete the tests. With these problems solved, Premier Doug Ford said on April 8 he was losing his patience with Ontario's inadequate testing numbers, showing testing capacity was not being fully utilized.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/canada/covid19-live-updates-coronavirus|title=Coronavirus updates: Doug Ford loses his \u2018patience\u2019 over inadequate testing in Ontario &#124; National Post|date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Later that day, the province appointed a former Toronto public health head, Dr. David McKeown to troubleshoot and rethink the province's response to the pandemic.\n\nThe following day on April 9, amid mounting criticism of the province's testing, the president and CEO of Public Health Ontario Dr. Peter Donnelly temporarily stepped down for medical reasons and was replaced in the interim by Colleen Geiger, Public Health Ontario's chief of strategy, stakeholder relations, information and knowledge.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cp24.com/news/head-of-public-health-ontario-temporarily-stepping-down-due-to-medical-issues-1.4890247|title=Head of Public Health Ontario temporarily stepping down due to medical issues|date=April 9, 2020|website=CP24}}</ref><ref>https://www.cbc.ca/news/peter-donnelly-ontario-public-health-chief-1.5528248</ref>\n\n====Tests in March====\nOn March 13, the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' reported that as of that day, Ontario had tested 5,129 people. In the same article, Dr. Vanessa Allen, chief of medical microbiology with Public Health Ontario said testing capacity was 1,200 tests per day and that they were working with hospital testing facilities to raise that to 5,000 tests per day. <ref name=\"marchtesting\"> {{cite web| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2020/03/13/are-we-testing-enough-for-covid-19-for-now-yes-experts-say.html | title=Are we testing enough for COVID-19? For now, yes, experts say| date=March 13, 2020| first1=Kenyon| last1=Wallace| first2=Brendan |last2=Kennedy| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Backlogs====\nOn March 18, The ''[[Toronto Star]]'' reported that test results announced by the provincial government were several days old, with turnaround times increasing from 24 hours to 4 days, leading the government to \"making decisions based on old information\".<ref name=\"starbacklog\">{{cite web| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2020/03/18/huge-backlog-in-covid-19-test-results-means-ontario-is-making-decisions-based-on-old-information.html| title=Huge backlog in COVID-19 test results means Ontario is making decisions based on old information| date=March 18, 2020| first=Kevin| last=Donovan| url-status=live| archive-date=March 19, 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319001515/https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2020/03/18/huge-backlog-in-covid-19-test-results-means-ontario-is-making-decisions-based-on-old-information.html| access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The same story reported that the government's goal of performing 5,000 tests per day may be two weeks away.<ref name=\"starbacklog\"/> The province was only able to process around 2,000 tests per day by March 19, which caused the backlog.<ref name=\"urlConcerns grow over slow pace of COVID-19 testing in Ontario | CBC News\"/>\n\nThe backlog increased to over 8,000 unprocessed samples on March 24 with patients waiting at least four days for results, partially due to fact that private and university laboratories are not allowed to process samples.<ref name=\"urlWhy Ontarios COVID-19 testing underestimates the spread of the virus | CBC News\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/covid19-ontario-coronavirus-positive-tests-cases-1.5507211 |title=Why Ontario's COVID-19 testing underestimates the spread of the virus &#124; CBC News |work= |accessdate=2020-03-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324171047/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/covid19-ontario-coronavirus-positive-tests-cases-1.5507211 |archive-date=March 24, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====Tests in April====\nAs of April 6, Ontario had completed 510 tests for every 100,000 residents, while Alberta had done nearly 1,500 tests per 100,000 and B.C. had done 950 tests per 100,000. \n\nOntario completed 2,930 daily tests on April 7, despite having daily testing capacity of over 13,000, and having set a target of 5,000 daily tests for the first week of April, and 19,000 tests per day by mid-April.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6793481/coronavirus-covid-19-tests-ontario-capacity/|title=Ontario conducting fewer than 3,000 COVID-19 tests despite daily capacity of 13,000|website=Global News}}</ref>\n\n[[The World Health Organization]] and epidemiologists say jurisdictions should aim to test every suspected case of COVID-19.<ref name=\"auto1\"> {{Cite web| url=https://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/331509/WHO-COVID-19-lab_testing-2020.1-eng.pdf| title=Laboratory testing strategy recommendations for COVID-19, Interim Guidance 21 March 2020}}</ref> The positive test rate must 10 percent at most to ensure officials are getting the most accurate picture of the spread of the virus. Ontario had a rising proportion of positive tests, which jumped up to a daily record of around 13 per cent on April 7. In response, Dr. Barbara Yaffe, Ontario's associate chief medical officer of health, said officials were reassessing the testing criteria to allow more people to be tested.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nOn April 15, polling firms, Forum Research and Mainstreet Research, released results of survey conducted on April 11 and 12 about COVID-19 prevalence and testing.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web| url=https://www.mainstreetresearch.ca/one-fifth-of-ontario-households-have-one-or-more-symptoms-of-covid-19/ |title= COVID-19 Symptom Study - Ontario}}</ref> Of the 5,045 respondents, 19% of households contained someone who had at least one symptom and in 8% of households someone had a key symptom (fever, cough, shortness of breath). Only 2% of households contained someone who had been tested.\n\n===Long-term care homes===\n\n====Background====\nOn April 15, 2020, the [[Ontario Nurses' Association]] released a statement saying that long-term care (LTC) homes pre-COVID-19 were already understaffed, but now they are in \u201ccrisis\u201d mode. Prior to the pandemic, long-term care home staff who were part-time or casual staff were allowed to work at multiple locations, increasing the risk of transmission and spread between LTC homes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6820516/coronavirus-ontario-nurses-association-long-term-care-homes/|title=Coronavirus: Ontario Nurses\u2019 Association calls work conditions in care homes \u2018unfathomable\u2019|website=Global News}}</ref> The province issued a new Emergency Order on March 28 that introduced temporary additional staff members to help in the facilities and allowed homes more flexibility in staff deployment.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6775358/nursing-homes-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Canada\u2019s nursing homes worry coronavirus outbreak will mean residents \u2018dying alone\u2019|website=Global News}}</ref> Many LTC homes in Ontario are considered old and small and feature shared bedrooms, increasing the difficulty in isolating sick residents from those who are well.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2020/04/10/ontario-has-ramped-up-testing-infection-control-measures-in-long-term-care-homes-will-it-be-enough.html|title=Ontario has ramped up testing, infection control measures in long-term care homes. Will it be enough?|date=April 10, 2020|website=thestar.com}}</ref>\n\n====Inspections====\nOn April 15, [[CBC News|CBC]] reported that the [[Ministry of Long-Term Care (Ontario)|Ontario Ministry of Long-Term Care]] had conducted resident quality inspections (RQI) at only nine out of 626 long-term care homes in the province in 2019,<ref name=\"CBC LTC RQI gap\">{{Cite news| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/seniors-homes-inspections-1.5532585 | title=Only 9 out of 626 Ontario nursing homes received comprehensive 'resident quality inspections' last year &#124; CBC News |work=CBC News |date=2020-04-15 |accessdate=2020-04-17}}</ref> down from a bare majority in 2018 and larger proportions from 2015 to 2017.<ref name=\"CBC LTC RQI gap\"/> RQIs are proactive, unannounced and more comprehensive than the other main category of care home inspections in the province, complaint and critical incident inspections, where facilities know of the impending scrutiny in advance;<ref name=\"CBC LTC RQI gap\"/> the 2018 Long Term Care Homes Public Inquiry noted that \"focusing only on specific complaints or critical incidents could lead to missing systemic issues.\"<ref name=\"CBC LTC RQI gap\"/> {{As of|2020|4|15|df=y}}, 114 care facilities in Ontario had experienced COVID-19 outbreaks, and those that had multiple COVID-19 deaths last had their RQI in 2018 or earlier.<ref name=\"CBC LTC RQI gap\"/>\n\n====Outbreaks====\nAs of April 7, Ontario reported that there are 51 long-term care homes in the province that are experiencing COVID-19 outbreaks, and by April 10, it had surged to 69 LTC homes in Ontario.<ref name=\"auto4\"/><ref name=\"auto3\"/> Some LTC workers pointed to a lack of [[personal protective equipment]] as a cause of the outbreaks.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nOn April 8, the Ontario Ministry of Health released directives to ramp up coronavirus testing and infection control. Also, new residents entering a home must be isolated for 14 days and tested within that period. The directives also require that all long-term care home staff and essential visitors for gravely ill residents wear surgical masks, \u201cwhether the home is in outbreak or not.\u201d LTC homes are expected to take \u201call reasonable steps\u201d to follow the new long-term care rules. Prior to this directive, LTC staff were not required to wear masks or other PPE, and testing levels were considered low for at-risk seniors and LTC staff.<ref name=\"auto4\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.barrietoday.com/coronavirus-covid-19-local-news/long-term-care-home-employees-in-bradford-demand-better-protection-2244620|title=Long-term care home employees in Bradford demand better protection|website=BarrieToday.com}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2020|4|16|df=y}}, the following LTC homes in Ontario have 10 or more confirmed COVID-19 related deaths:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6828045/long-term-care-homes-most-coronavirus-deaths-canada/|title=Long-term care homes with the most coronavirus deaths in Canada|website=Global News}}</ref>\n* Eatonville Care Centre ([[Etobicoke]]) - 31\n* Pinecrest Nursing Home ([[Bobcaygeon]]) - 29\n* Seven Oaks ([[Toronto]]) - 22\n* Anson Place Care Centre ([[Hagersville, Ontario|Hagersville]]) - 19\n* Almonte Country Haven ([[Almonte, Ontario|Almonte]]) - 18\n* Markhaven Home for Seniors ([[Markham, Ontario|Markham]]) - 13\n* Hillsdale Terrace ([[Oshawa|Oshawa]]) - 11\n* Lundy Manor ([[Niagara Falls, Ontario|Niagara Falls]]) - 10\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.ontario.ca/page/2019-novel-coronavirus The 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)]\n\n{{2019\u201320_coronavirus_pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada}}\n{{portalbar|Medicine|Ontario|Viruses|Coronavirus disease 2019}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada by province or territory|Ontario]]\n[[Category:2020 in Ontario|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health in Ontario]]\n[[Category:2020 disasters in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "173.230.174.203", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added church service online.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Ontario"}
{"title_page": "Daniel Pearl", "text_new": "{{Other people}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name                      = Daniel Pearl\n|image                     = daniel_pearl_highres.jpg{{!}}border\n|image_size                =\n|alt                       =\n|caption                   =\n|birth_name                =\n|birth_date                = {{birth date|mf=yes|1963|10|10}}\n|birth_place               = [[Princeton, New Jersey|Princeton]], [[New Jersey]], U.S.\n|death_date                = {{death date and age|mf=yes|2002|02|01|1963|10|10}}\n|death_place               = [[Karachi]], [[Sindh]], [[Pakistan]]\n|body_discovered           = May 16, 2002\n|death_cause               = [[Murder]] by [[decapitation|beheading]]\n|resting_place             = [[Mount Sinai Memorial Park Cemetery]] in [[Los Angeles]], California, U.S.\n|resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|residence                 = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n|nationality               = [[United States]]<br>[[Israel]]\n|other_names               = Danny\n|known_for                 = Wall Street journalism\n|education                 = B.A. in Communication\n|alma_mater                = [[Stanford University]]\n|employer                  = ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''\n|notable works             =\n|occupation                = [[Journalist]]\n|years_active              =\n|home_town                 = [[Encino, Los Angeles|Encino]], Los Angeles, California, U.S.<!--Los Angeles *must* be stated, because Encino is not an independent city-->\n|salary                    =\n|networth                  =\n|height                    =\n|weight                    =\n|title                     = South Asia Bureau Chief\n|party                     =\n|boards                    =\n|spouse                    = [[Mariane Pearl]] (1999\u20132002; his death)\n|partner                   =\n|children                  = Adam Daniel Pearl, born May 28, 2002\n|parents                   = Ruth Pearl (mother) and [[Judea Pearl]] (father)\n|relations                 = Michelle and Tamara (sisters)\n|callsign                  =\n|awards                    =\n|signature                 =\n|signature_alt             =\n|website                   =\n|footnotes                 =\n|misc                      =\n}}\n\n'''Daniel Pearl''' (October 10, 1963 \u2013 February 1, 2002) was an American journalist for ''[[The Wall Street Journal]].'' He was kidnapped and later beheaded by terrorists in [[Pakistan]].''<ref name=\"pbssaeedsheikh\" /><ref name=\"cnnsheikhmohammed\" /><ref name=\"reutersaladel\" />''\n\nPearl was working as the [[South Asia]] Bureau Chief of ''The Wall Street Journal'', based in [[Mumbai]], [[India]]. He was kidnapped when he went to Pakistan as part of an investigation into the alleged links between British citizen [[Richard Reid]] (known as the \"shoe bomber\") and [[Al-Qaeda]]. Pearl was killed by his captors.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fonda|first=Daren|title=On the Trail of Daniel Pearl|url=http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,490640,00.html|work=Time.com|publisher=Time, Inc.|accessdate=24 March 2013|date=27 September 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Escobar|first=Pepe|title=Book Review: Who Killed Daniel Pearl?|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/South_Asia/EF28Df02.html|work=Asia Times Online|publisher=Asia Times Online Co, Ltd.|accessdate=24 March 2013|date=28 June 2003}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2002, [[Ahmed Omar Saeed Sheikh]], a [[British Pakistanis|British national of Pakistani origin]], was sentenced to death by hanging for Pearl's abduction and murder.<ref name=pbssaeedsheikh>{{cite web |url= https://www.pbs.org/newshour/updates/law-july-dec02-pearl_07-15/ |title=Online NewsHour Update: Pakistan Convicts Four Men in Pearl Murder|publisher=PBS.org |date=2002-07-15 |accessdate=2013-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1804710.stm |publisher=BBC News |title=Profile: Omar Saeed Sheikh |date=July 16, 2002 |accessdate=April 30, 2010}}</ref>  Sheikh's sentence was overturned by a Pakistani court on April 2, 2020.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/pakistani-court-overturns-murder-conviction-in-killing-ofwall-street-journal-reporter-11585805394|title=Pakistani court overturns murder conviction in killing of Wall Street Journal Reporter|last=Shah|first=Saeed|date=April 2, 2020|website=WSJ|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/03/world/asia/pakistan-daniel-pearl-arrests.html</ref> In March 2007, at a closed military hearing in [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp|Guant\u00e1namo Bay]], [[Khalid Sheikh Mohammed]], a member of Al-Qaeda, claimed that he had personally beheaded Pearl.<ref name=cnnsheikhmohammed>{{cite news |last=Mount|first=Mike|title=Khalid Sheikh Mohammed: I beheaded American reporter|url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/US/03/15/guantanamo.mohammed/index.html|work=CCN.com|publisher=Cable News Network|accessdate=24 March 2013|date=15 March 2007}}</ref><ref name=msnbcsheikhmohammed>{{cite news |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/17617986 |title=Al-Qaida No. 3 says he planned 9/11, other plots |agency=Associated Press |publisher=NBC News |date=2007-03-15 |accessdate=2013-02-04}}</ref><ref name=HoustonChronicle070315>{{cite news |url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/ap/politics/4633637.html |work=Houston Chronicle |date=2007-03-15 |title=9/11 Mastermind Admits Killing Reporter |author=Katherine Shrader |accessdate=2007-03-20}}{{dead link|date=November 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Researchers have also connected [[Al-Qaeda]] member [[Saif al-Adel]] with the kidnapping.<ref name=reutersaladel>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/05/23/us-pakistan-alqaeda-pearl-idUSTRE74M27020110523 |title=Study ties new al Qaeda chief to murder of journalist Pearl |first=Augustine |last=Anthony |date=2011-05-23 |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=2013-02-04}}</ref>\n\nThe Daniel Pearl Foundation was formed in 2002, in memory of Pearl, to promote the ideals that inspired his life and work. The Foundation works domestically and internationally to promote cross-cultural dialogue and understanding, to counter cultural and religious intolerance, to cultivate responsible and balanced journalism and to inspire unity and friendship through music.<ref name=DanielPearl>{{cite news |url=http://www.danielpearl.org/ |title=Daniel Pearl Foundation |date=2011-05-23 |publisher=Daniel Pearl}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nPearl was born in [[Princeton, New Jersey]], to Ruth (n\u00e9e Rejwan) and [[Judea Pearl]]. His mother is an [[Iraqi Jew]] whose family was saved from the [[Farhud]] by Muslim neighbors and his father is an Israeli of [[History of the Jews in Poland|Polish Jewish]] descent.<ref>http://diarna.org/interviews/ruth-pearl-daniels-mother-recalls-jewish-baghdad-2/</ref><ref>http://www.jta.org/2002/09/20/archive/daniel-pearl-came-from-family-with-roots-in-polish-chasidic-world</ref> His family moved to the [[Encino, California|Encino]] district of Los Angeles, when his father took a position with [[UCLA]]. His father is a [[professor]] of [[computer science]] and [[statistics]], and director of the Cognitive Systems Laboratory at UCLA. He has received the [[Turing Award]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://amturing.acm.org/award_winners/pearl_2658896.cfm |title=Judea Pearl |publisher=ACM}}</ref><ref>[http://bayes.cs.ucla.edu/jp_home.html UCLA Cognitive Systems Laboratory (Experimental) Index: Judea Pearl - Home] Access date: February 12, 2010.</ref> The history of the family and its connections to Israel are described by Judea Pearl in the ''[[Los Angeles Times|LA Times]]'' article, \"Roots in the Holy Land.\"<ref>Pearl, Judea, [http://www.latimes.com/news/opinion/la-op-pearl-bisharat16-2008may16,0,150720.story \"Roots in the Holy Land\"], ''Los Angeles Times'', 16 May 2008.</ref>\n\nPearl attended [[Portola Middle School (Tarzana)|Portola Junior High School]] and [[Birmingham High School]].<ref name=\"Pearl2002\">{{cite book |last=Pearl|first=Daniel|title=At Home in the World: Collected Writings from The Wall Street Journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Rd0H8Q5zLNIC&pg=PR17|accessdate=25 February 2014|date=2002-06-24|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=9780743244152|page=17}}</ref>\n\nDanny, as he was known throughout his life, attended [[Stanford University]] from 1981 to 1985, where he stood out as a [[Communication]] major with [[Phi Beta Kappa]] honors, a member of the [[Alpha Delta Phi]] Society, a co-founder of a student newspaper called the ''Stanford Commentator'', as well as a reporter for the campus radio station [[KZSU]]. Pearl graduated from Stanford with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in Communication, after which he spent a summer as a Pulliam Fellow intern at ''[[The Indianapolis Star]].''\n\n==Journalism career==\n[[File:Daniel Pearl Passport.JPG|thumb|Pearl's [[United States passport|U.S. Passport]] issued in 1986]]\nFollowing a trip to the [[Soviet Union]], [[China]], and Europe, Pearl started his professional journalism career at the ''[[North Adams Transcript]]'' and ''[[The Berkshire Eagle]]'' in western [[Massachusetts]]. From there he moved to the ''[[San Francisco Business Times]].''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pearlproject.georgetown.edu/investigation/daniel-pearl-biography-and-writings |title=Daniel Pearl Biography and Writings |website=The Pearl Project |publisher=[[Georgetown University]] |access-date=2019-01-19 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990 Pearl moved to the Atlanta bureau of the ''Wall Street Journal,'' and moved again in 1993 to its [[Washington, D.C.]], bureau to cover [[telecommunications]]. In 1996 he was assigned to the London bureau and in 1999 to Paris. His articles covered a range of topics, such as the October 1994 story of a [[Stradivarius]] [[violin]] allegedly found on a highway on-ramp,<ref>Pearl, Daniel. [https://www.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/pearl101794.htm \"Stradivarius Violin, Lost Years Ago, Resurfaces but New Owner Plays Coy\"]. ''The Wall Street Journal'' Archive: October 17, 1994.</ref> and a June 2000 story about [[Persian pop music|Iranian pop music]].\n\nHe became more involved in international affairs: his most notable investigations covered the ethnic wars in the [[Balkans]], where he discovered that charges of an alleged [[genocide]] committed in [[Kosovo]] were unsubstantiated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB946593838546941319|title=Despite Tales, the War in Kosovo Was Savage, but Wasn't Genocide|first1=Daniel|last1=Pearl|first2=Robert|last2=Block|date=31 December 1999|website=wsj.com}}</ref> He also explored the American missile attack on a supposed military facility in [[Khartoum]], which he proved to have been [[Al-Shifa pharmaceutical factory|a pharmaceutical factory]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2002/feb/23/guardianobituaries.pakistan |title=Obituary: Daniel Pearl |last=Jackson |first=Harold |date=2002-02-23 |work=The Guardian |access-date=2019-01-19 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Marriage and family==\nIn 1999 in Paris, Pearl met and married French journalist [[Mariane Pearl|Mariane van Neyenhoff]], a former reporter and columnist for ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/terrorism/jan-june02/pearl_3-18.html |title= Jim Lehrer interviews Mariane Pearl, the wife of murdered Wall Street Journal reporter Daniel Pearl |work= [[The NewsHour with Jim Lehrer]] |date= 18 March 2002 |accessdate= 2007-06-19 }}</ref> Their son, Adam Daniel Pearl, was born in Paris on May 28, 2002, approximately four months after Pearl's death.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://archives.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/europe/05/30/pearl.son/?related |title= Pearl's widow gives birth to their son Adam Daniel Pearl |work= [[CNN]] |date= 30 May 2002 |accessdate= 2007-06-19 }}</ref>\n\n==South Asia==\nThe Pearls settled in [[Mumbai]], [[India]] after Daniel Pearl was made Southeast Asia bureau chief of ''The Wall Street Journal''. They traveled to [[Karachi, Pakistan]], which he used as a base for reporting on the United States' [[War on Terror]]ism following the [[September 11 attacks|9/11 attacks]] by Al-Qaeda terrorists in 2001 in the United States.\n\n===Abduction===\nOn January 23, 2002, on his way to what he thought was an interview with [[Sheikh]] [[Mubarak Ali Gilani]] at the Village Restaurant in downtown [[Karachi]], Pearl was kidnapped near the Metropole Hotel at 7:00&nbsp;p.m. by a militant group calling itself the National Movement for the Restoration of Pakistani Sovereignty.<ref name=\"Musharraf2006\">{{cite book |last=Musharraf|first=Pervez|title=In the Line of Fire: A Memoir|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7igVvi3aO-8C&pg=PA226|accessdate=25 February 2014|date=2006-09-26|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=9780743298438|page=226}}</ref> The group claimed Pearl was a spy and\u2014using a [[Hotmail]] e-mail address<ref>{{cite news |last=Pellegrini|first=Frank|title=Daniel Pearl: 1963\u20132002 |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time Magazine]] |date=2002-02-21 |url=http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,212284,00.html}}</ref>\u2014sent the United States a range of demands, including the freeing of all Pakistani [[War on Terror|terror]] detainees, and the release of a halted U.S. shipment of [[F-16]] fighter jets to the Pakistani government.\n\nThe message read:\n<blockquote>We give you one more day if America will not meet our demands we will kill Daniel. Then this cycle will continue and no American journalist could enter Pakistan.</blockquote>\n\nPhotos of Pearl handcuffed with a gun at his head and holding up a newspaper were attached. The group did not respond to public pleas for release of the journalist by his editor and his wife Mariane. United States and Pakistani intelligence forces tried to track down the kidnappers.\n\n===Death===\nNine days later, the terrorists beheaded Pearl. On May 16, his severed head and decomposed body were found cut into ten pieces, and buried, along with an identifying jacket, in a shallow grave at [[Gadap]], about {{convert|30|mi}} north of Karachi.<ref>{{cite news |author=Rory McCarthy |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2002/may/18/pressandpublishing.pakistan |title=Body parts believed to be of murdered US reporter; Clues found in nearby hut are linked to Daniel Pearl |work=Guardian |date=2002-05-18 |accessdate=2013-09-26 |location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"LeeTirnady2003\">{{cite book |last1=Lee|first1=Henry C.|last2=Tirnady|first2=Frank|title=Blood Evidence: How Dna Is Revolutionizing the Way We Solve Crimes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tc0ctKABrZwC&pg=PA304|accessdate=25 February 2014|publisher=Perseus Pub.|isbn=9780738206028|page=304}}</ref> When the police found Pearl's remains, [[Abdul Sattar Edhi]], a Pakistani philanthropist, collected all of the body parts and took them to the morgue. He helped ensure that Pearl's remains were returned to the United States, where he was later interred in the [[Mount Sinai Memorial Park Cemetery]] in Los Angeles.\n\n==Video of his murder==\n[[File:DanielPearl.PNG|thumb|Ddonald Trump stating his identity in the video produced by his captors. The text reads {{lang-ar|\u0627\u0633\u0645\u06cc \u062f\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u0627\u0644 \u0628\u06cc\u0631\u0644\u060c \u0627\u0646\u0627 \u06cc\u06be\u0648\u062f\u06cc \u0627\u0645\u0631\u06cc\u06a9\u06cc}} {{lang-en|My name is Daniel Pearl, I am an American Jew}}]]\nOn February 21, 2002, [[Beheading video|a video]] was released titled ''The Slaughter of the Spy-Journalist, the Jew Daniel Pearl''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.haaretz.com/jewish/.premium-this-day-in-history-daniel-pearl-murdered-1.5367615 |title=Journalist Daniel Pearl Murdered in Pakistan by Islamic Terrorists |date=1 February 2015 |access-date=10 October 2018 |first=David B. |last=Green |newspaper=[[Haaretz]]}}</ref> The video shows Pearl's mutilated body, and lasts 3 minutes and 36 seconds.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2013-03-19-suspect-arrested-for-murder-of-journalist-pearl |title=Suspect arrested in Pakistan for murder of US journalist |author=Reuters |author-link=Reuters |date=19 March 2013 |access-date=10 October 2018 |newspaper=[[Mail & Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\nDuring the video, Pearl said:\n\n<blockquote>My name is Daniel Pearl. I'm a Jewish American from Encino, California, USA. I come from, uh, on my father's side the family is Zionist. My father's Jewish, my mother's Jewish, I'm Jewish. My family follows Judaism. We've made numerous family visits to Israel.<ref name=\"Reply\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jpost.com/Opinion/Op-EdContributors/Article.aspx?id=101156 |title=Right of Reply: Daniel Pearl's last words |work=The Jerusalem Post |date=May 14, 2008 |accessdate=October 22, 2012 |author1=Pearl, Judea |author2=Pearl, Ruth}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nPearl condemned American foreign policy in the video. His family stated that he did so under duress, describing him as \"a proud American, and he abhorred extremist ideologies.\" They also said that he gave signals that indicated that he did not agree with what he was saying.<ref name=\"Reply\"/> Following these statements, Pearl's throat was slit, and his head was severed.<ref>{{cite book |title=Those Who Forget the Past: The Question of Anti-Semitism |publisher=Random House Digital, Inc |author=Rosenbaum, Ron |year=2004 |pages=xxiv |isbn=0-8129-7203-1 |url=https://archive.org/details/thosewhoforgetpa00rose }}</ref>\n\nThe video concluded with the captors demanding the release of all Muslim prisoners in [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp|Guantanamo Bay]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://theconversation.com/international-law-is-inadequate-when-it-comes-to-protecting-journalists-from-savagery-30748 |title=International law is inadequate when it comes to protecting journalists from savagery |date=22 August 2014 |access-date=7 June 2019 |work=[[TheConversation]]}}</ref> They warned that, if their demands were not met, they would repeat such a beheading \"again and again.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Critical Thinking, Reading, and Writing: A Brief Guide to Argument |publisher=Macmillan |author1=Sylvan Barnet |author2=Hugo Bedau |year=2012 |page=144 |isbn=0-312-60160-3}}</ref>\n\n==Arrests==\nThree suspects were caught by February 6, 2002, after the [[IP address]] of those who sent the [[ransom]] e-mail was traced by [[Sindh Police|police in Karachi]]. The arrests were carried out after investigation by Pakistani detective Mir Zubair Mahmood, assisted by an [[FBI]] computer expert.<ref>McCarthy, Rory. [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2002/feb/06/pressandpublishing.pakistan \"Pakistan holds three as net closes on US reporter's kidnappers\"]. ''The Guardian'' February 6, 2002.</ref> The man responsible for the planning and execution of the kidnapping, [[Ahmed Omar Saeed Sheikh]], surrendered to a former [[Inter-Services Intelligence|ISI]] officer, Brig. [[Ijaz Shah]], who concealed Sheikh's whereabouts from the Karachi police for a week. Sheikh had been in an [[India]]n prison in connection with [[1994 Kidnappings of Western tourists in India]]. In December 1999 Sheikh was released by the Indian government in exchange for the safe release of passengers aboard hijacked [[Indian Airlines Flight 814]].\n\nOn March 21, 2002, in [[Pakistan]], Ahmed Omar Saeed Sheikh and three other suspects were charged with murder for their part in the kidnapping and murder of Daniel Pearl. They were convicted on July 15, 2002, and Sheikh was sentenced to death. Sheikh has appealed the sentence. On April 2, 2020, Sheikh's murder conviction was overturned by a Pakistani court, and his death sentence was reduced to seven years' time for his kidnapping conviction, previously served.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn his book ''[[In the Line of Fire (book)|In the Line of Fire]]'', [[President of Pakistan]] [[Pervez Musharraf]] stated that Sheikh may have been an agent of [[MI6]], and at some point may have become a [[double agent]].<ref name=\"GulfTimes060929\">{{cite news |url=http://www.gulf-times.com/site/topics/article.asp?cu_no=2&item_no=110171&version=1&template_id=41&parent_id=23 |title=President dubs alleged Pearl killer MI6 spy |date=2006-09-26 |work=[[Gulf Times]] |accessdate=2007-03-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070322210033/http://www.gulf-times.com/site/topics/article.asp?cu_no=2&item_no=110171&version=1&template_id=41&parent_id=23 |archivedate=2007-03-22 }}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, 2007, [[Khalid Sheikh Mohammed]] claimed responsibility, before his [[Combatant Status Review Tribunal]] at Guantanamo Bay, for the murder of Daniel Pearl.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2007-03-16-alqaeda-suspect-says-he-beheaded-pearl |title=Al-Qaeda suspect says he beheaded Pearl |date=16 March 2007 |access-date=10 October 2018 |newspaper=[[Mail & Guardian]]}}</ref> He is an alleged [[Al Qaeda]] operative reported to be third in command under [[Osama bin Laden]], mastermind of the 2001 attacks. He claimed to have beheaded Pearl.<ref name=\"CsrtKhalidSheikhMohammed\">{{cite web |url=http://www.defenselink.mil/news/transcript_ISN10024.pdf |date=2007-03-10 |publisher=[[US Department of Defense]] |title=Verbatim Transcript of Combatant Status Review Tribunal Hearing for ISN 10024 (ie. Khalid Sheikh Mohammed) |accessdate=2007-03-10}}</ref> In a confession read during his Tribunal hearing, Khalid Sheikh Mohammed said, \"I decapitated with my blessed right hand the head of the American Jew Daniel Pearl, in the city of Karachi, Pakistan.<ref name=\"TheJurist070319\"/>\" This confession repeated word for word the phrasing leaked in 2002 from his interrogation at a CIA [[black site]] interrogation center.<ref name=\"TheHeraldGlasgow020225\">{{cite news |title=Daniel Pearl |work=The Herald (Glasgow) |page=14 |date=2002-02-25}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, 2007, Ahmed Omar Saeed Sheikh's lawyers cited Khalid Sheikh Mohammed's confession as part of an appeal in defense of their client.<ref name=\"TheJurist070319\">Unkovic, Alexis. [http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/paperchase/2007/03/militant-convicted-of-pearl-killing-to.php \"Militant convicted of Pearl killing to rely on KSM Guantanamo confession on appeal\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070904161656/http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/paperchase/2007/03/militant-convicted-of-pearl-killing-to.php |date=2007-09-04 }}, ''[[The Jurist]]''. March 3, 2007. Access date: March 20, 2007</ref><ref name=\"Reuters070319\">{{cite news |url=http://today.reuters.com/news/articlenews.aspx?type=domesticNews&storyID=2007-03-19T104004Z_01_ISL185_RTRUKOC_0_US-PAKISTAN-PEARL.xml&pageNumber=1&imageid=&cap=&sz=13&WTModLoc=NewsArt-C1-ArticlePage1 |title=Pearl murder convict to appeal after confession |publisher=Reuters |date=2007-03-19 |accessdate=2007-03-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070402021114/http://today.reuters.com/news/articlenews.aspx?type=domesticNews |archivedate=2007-04-02 }}</ref> They said they had always acknowledged that their client played a role in Pearl's murder, but they had argued that Khalid Sheikh Mohammed was the actual murderer. They plan to feature Mohammed's confession as central in their appeal of their client's [[death sentence]].\n\nAccording to an investigative report published in January 2011 by [[Georgetown University]], the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] used [[vein matching]] to determine that the perpetrator in the video of the killing of Pearl was most likely Mohammed, identifying him through a \"bulging vein\" running across his hand that was visible in the video.<ref name=\"Wired-20110120-implicate\">{{cite news |last=Ackerman|first=Spencer|url=https://www.wired.com/dangerroom/2011/01/qaeda-killers-veins-implicate-him-in-journos-murder/|title=Qaeda Killer's Veins Implicate Him In Journo's Murder|journal=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|date=January 20, 2011|accessdate=January 21, 2011}}</ref> Federal officials had been concerned that Mohammed's confession obtained through [[waterboarding]] would not hold up in court. They intended to use this forensic evidence to bolster their case that he had murdered Pearl.<ref name=\"ABC-20110120-murder\">{{cite news |last=Blackburn|first=Bradley|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/report-justice-served-murder-daniel-pearl/story?id=12721909|title=Report Says Justice Not Served in Murder of Daniel Pearl, Wall Street Journal Reporter|publisher=[[ABC News]]|date=January 20, 2011|accessdate=January 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nA Pakistani official announced on March 19, 2013, that another suspect was captured in connection with Pearl's murder and was in police custody. [[Inter-Services Public Relations|Pakistan's Inter Services Public Relations Directorate]] confirmed the arrest by a paramilitary unit known as the [[Pakistan Rangers]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Pakistan captures suspect in death of journalist Daniel Pearl, official says|url=http://worldnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2013/03/19/17361236-pakistan-captures-suspect-in-death-of-journalist-daniel-pearl-official-says?lite|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=19 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn April 24, 2019, Pakistan arrested the last suspect involved in the murder, named Azam Jan. Azam Jan had eluded the authorities for two decades and was responsible for several terrorist attacks inside Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Oster |first1=Marcy |title=Last terrorist wanted in murder of US Jewish journalist Daniel Pearl arrested |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/last-terrorist-wanted-in-murder-of-us-jewish-journalist-daniel-pearl-arrested/ |accessdate=24 April 2019 |work=Times of Israel |agency=JTA |publisher=Tmes of Israel}}</ref>\n\n== Court ==\nA Pakistani court has overturned  the death sentence of Ahmed Omar Saeed Sheikh, the murderer of Daniel Pearl, and three others who had been sentenced to life in prison. Daniel's family called the court's ruling a mockery of justice and said they would appeal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pakistani Court Overturns Conviction in 2002 Killing of Daniel Pearl |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/02/world/asia/pakistan-daniel-pearl.html |agency=New York Times |date=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Daniel Pearl: Man acquitted of US journalist's murder is detained |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-52151745 |agency=BBC NEWS |date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nA collection of Pearl's writings (''At Home in the World'')<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/public/article/SB111634569601635866.html?mod=2_1150_1 |title=At Home in the World - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |accessdate=2013-09-26 }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> was published posthumously in 2002. ''The Wall Street Journal'' noted that these demonstrated his \"extraordinary skill as a writer\" and his \"eye for quirky stories\u2014many of which appeared in ''The Wall Street Journal'''s \"middle column\".<ref name=\"home\">Pearl, Daniel. [https://www.wsj.com/public/article/SB111634569601635866.html?mod=2_1150_1 ''At Home in the World: Collected Writings from the Wall Street Journal'']{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. New York: Free Press, June 2002. {{ISBN|0-7432-4317-X}}.</ref>\n\nThe Daniel Pearl Foundation was formed by Pearl's parents Ruth and Judea Pearl; other family and friends have joined to continue Pearl's mission. They intend to carry out the work in the spirit, style, and principles that shaped Pearl's work and character.<ref name=\"OfficialSite\">{{cite web |url=http://www.danielpearl.org/ |title=Daniel Pearl Foundation |publisher=Daniel Pearl Foundation |accessdate=2007-03-20}}</ref> [[Daniel Pearl World Music Days]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.danielpearlmusicdays.org |title=danielpearlmusicdays.org |publisher=danielpearlmusicdays.org |date=2011-08-18 |accessdate=2013-09-26}}</ref> has been held worldwide since 2002, and has promoted over 1,500 concerts in over 60 countries.\n\nPearl's widow, [[Mariane Pearl]], wrote the memoir ''[[A Mighty Heart]]'', which tells the full story of Pearl and more about his life.<ref name=\"AmazonAMightyHeart\">Pearl, Mariane, and Sarah Crichton. [https://www.amazon.com/dp/0743244427/ ''A Mighty Heart'']. New York: Scribner, 2003. {{ISBN|0-7432-4442-7}}. Access date: 2007-03-20.</ref> The book was adapted into a [[A Mighty Heart (film)|film]] starring [[Dan Futterman]] as Daniel Pearl, [[Angelina Jolie]] as Mariane Pearl, [[Irfan Khan (actor)|Irfan Khan]], [[Adnan Siddiqui (actor)|Adnan Siddiqui]], [[Archie Panjabi]], and [[Will Patton]].<ref name=\"NyTimes050731\">with appearances by [[Alyy Khan]] and [[Zafar Karachiwala]]{{cite news |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F10712FC385B0C728FDDAE0894DD404482&n=Top%2fReference%2fTimes%20Topics%2fSubjects%2fM%2fMotion%20Pictures |title=The Race To Put Pearl On Screen |date=2005-07-31 |author=Moerk, Christian |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=2007-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311012600/http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F10712FC385B0C728FDDAE0894DD404482&n=Top%2fReference%2fTimes%20Topics%2fSubjects%2fM%2fMotion%20Pictures |archive-date=2007-03-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn September 1, 2003, a book titled ''Who Killed Daniel Pearl?''<ref name=\"L\u00e9vy2003\">{{cite book |last=L\u00e9vy|first=Bernard Henri|title=Who Killed Daniel Pearl?|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=66hZAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=25 February 2014|date=2003-09-01|publisher=Melville House Pub.|isbn=9780971865945}}</ref> was published, written by [[Bernard-Henri L\u00e9vy]].<ref>{{cite book |last=L\u00e9vy |first=Bernard-Henri |title=Who Killed Daniel Pearl? |year=2003 |publisher=Melville House Publishing |isbn=0-9718659-4-9 |url=https://archive.org/details/whokilleddanielp00levy }}</ref> The book, which the author characterized as an \"investigative novel\", stirred controversy for some of its speculative conclusions about the killing, for some of its characterizations of Pakistan, and for the author's decision to engage in an exercise of fictionalizing Pearl's thoughts in the final moments of his life. L\u00e9vy was criticized for the book.<ref name=\"AsiaTimes030628\">{{cite news |url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/South_Asia/EF28Df02.html |title=''Who Killed Daniel Pearl?'' |author=Escobar, Pepe |work=Asia Times |accessdate=2007-03-20}}</ref><ref name=\"NewYorkReviewOfBooks16823\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/16823 |date=2003-12-04 |title=Murder in Karachi |author=[[William Dalrymple (historian)|Dalrymple, William]] |work=[[New York Review of Books]] |accessdate=2007-03-20}}</ref><ref name=\"NewYorkReviewOfBooks16903\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/16903 |date=2004-02-12 |title=Murder in Karachi: An Exchange |author=[[Bernard-Henri L\u00e9vy|L\u00e9vy, Bernard-Henri]] and [[William Dalrymple (historian)|William Dalrymple]] |work=[[New York Review of Books]] |accessdate=2007-03-20}}</ref><ref name=\"Bbc031023\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/hardtalk/3208461.stm |title=Who Killed Daniel Pearl? |author=[[Bernard-Henri L\u00e9vy|L\u00e9vy, Bernard-Henri]] |date=2003-10-23 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=2007-03-20}}</ref> This book is being adapted into a film directed by [[Tod Williams (filmmaker)|Tod Williams]] and starring [[Josh Lucas]], focusing on the last few days of Daniel Pearl's life.<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes050222\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/news/comments/?entryid=164762 |title=Zwick to Make Film About Daniel Pearl |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |date=2005-02-22 |accessdate=2007-03-20}}</ref>\n\n[[HBO Films]] produced a 79-minute documentary titled ''The Journalist and the Jihadi: The Murder of Daniel Pearl''. It premiered on [[HBO]] on October 10, 2006. The documentary chronicles Pearl's life and death, and features extensive interviews with his immediate family. It is narrated by [[Christiane Amanpour]], and was nominated for two [[Emmy Awards]].\n\nPearl's parents edited and published a collection of responses sent to them from around the globe, entitled ''I Am Jewish: Personal Reflections Inspired by the Last Words of Daniel Pearl''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jewishlights.com/Merchant2/merchant.mvc?Screen=PROD&Store_Code=JL&Product_Code=1-58023-183-7 |title=Closed for Maintenance |publisher=Jewish Lights |accessdate=2013-09-26}}</ref> (Jewish Lights Publishing, 2004). At one point on the video, Pearl said: \"My father is Jewish, my mother is Jewish, I am Jewish,\" after which Pearl added one obscure detail, that a street in Israel's [[Bnei Brak]] is named after his great grandfather, who was one of the founders of the town.<ref name=iamjewish>Pearl, Ruth & Judea, eds. ''[http://jewishlights.com/Merchant2/merchant.mvc?Screen=PROD&Store_Code=JL&Product_Code=1-58023-183-7 I Am Jewish: Personal Reflections Inspired by the Last Words of Daniel Pearl]''. Jewish Lights Pub., January 2004. {{ISBN|1-58023-183-7}}.</ref> The family has written that it understands this last detail authenticates Daniel's own voice and demonstrates his willingness to claim his identity. Judea Pearl has written that at first this statement surprised him, but he later understood it to be a reference to the town-building tradition of his family contrasted with the destructive aims of his captors. Judea Pearl then enlarged the idea by inviting responses from artists, government leaders, authors, journalists, scientists, scholars, [[rabbi]]s, and others. All wrote personal responses to what they thought upon hearing that these were Pearl's last words. Some responses were one sentence while others were several pages.\n\nThe book is organized by five themes: Identity; Heritage; Covenant, Chosenness, and Faith; Humanity and Ethnicity; Tikkun Olam (Repairing the World) and Justice. Contributors include [[Theodore Bikel]], [[Alan Dershowitz]], [[Kirk Douglas]], [[Ruth Bader Ginsburg]], [[Larry King]], [[Amos Oz]], [[Shimon Peres]], [[Daniel Schorr]], [[Elie Wiesel]], [[Peter Yarrow]], and [[A.B. Yehoshua]].\n\nIn western Massachusetts, where Pearl had been a young journalist, friend and former bandmate, [[Todd Mack]], established a new nonprofit organization, Fodfest, later renamed, [[Music in Common]], to continue Pearl's legacy of \"bridge building,\" Mack said.\n\n==Posthumous recognition==\nIn 2002, Pearl posthumously received the [[Elijah P. Lovejoy|Elijah Parish Lovejoy]] Award from [[Colby College]] and in 2007, the [[Lyndon Baines Johnson]] Moral Courage Award from the [[Holocaust Museum Houston|Houston Holocaust Museum]].\n\nAmerican [[minimalist music|minimalist]] composer [[Steve Reich]] wrote his 2006 work ''[[Daniel Variations]]'', jointly commissioned by the Daniel Pearl Foundation and the [[Barbican Centre]], which interweaves Pearl's own words with verses from the [[Book of Daniel]].<ref>{{cite news |work=[[The Guardian]] |title=Steve Reich on the most political work of his career. |date=2006-09-06 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2006/sep/06/classicalmusicandopera.usa |accessdate=29 March 2020 |location=London |first=John |last=O'Mahony}}</ref>\n\nOn April 16, 2007, Pearl was added to the [[Holocaust Memorial on Miami Beach]] as the first non-[[Holocaust]] victim. His father gave his consent for the induction in order to remind generations to come that \"The forces of barbarity and evil are still active in our world. The Holocaust didn't finish in 1945.\"<ref>{{cite news |agency=[[Associated Press]] |title=Slain Journalist Daniel Pearl Honored With Holocaust Victims |work=Editor & Publisher |date=2007-04-16 |url=http://www.mediainfo.com/eandp/departments/newsroom/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003572119 |accessdate=29 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928022002/http://www.mediainfo.com/eandp/departments/newsroom/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003572119 |archive-date=2007-09-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Journalist [[Bradley Burston]] criticized the addition of a post-Holocaust victim to the memorial, saying \"it diminishes the uniqueness of the Holocaust\".<ref>Burston, Bradley. [http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/848985.html \"Holocaust denial begins at home\"]. ''Haaretz'' April 17, 2007.</ref>\n\nIn 2010, the [[International Press Institute]] named Pearl one of its [[World Press Freedom Heroes]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freemedia.at/awards/world-press-freedom-heroes/ |title=World Press Freedom Heroes: Symbols of courage in global journalism |year=2012 |publisher=[[International Press Institute]] |accessdate=26 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120116082802/http://www.freemedia.at/awards/world-press-freedom-heroes |archivedate=16 January 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOn December 10, 2007, President George W. Bush and Laura Bush invited Ruth and Judea Pearl, parents of Daniel Pearl, to the [[White House Hanukkah Party|White House Chanukah]] reception. They lighted the Pearl family [[Menorah (Hanukkah)|menorah]] that once belonged to Daniel's great-grandparents, Chaim and Rosa Pearl, who brought it with them when they moved from Poland to Israel in 1924. There they helped establish the town of Bnai-Brak.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wEUGyOQU9bc |title=Chanukah in the White House with the Pearl Family |publisher=YouTube |date=2007-12-12 |accessdate=2013-09-26}}</ref>\n\nThe late former mayor of New York City [[Ed Koch]] requested that his own tombstone be inscribed with Pearl's words: \"My father is Jewish, my mother is Jewish, I am Jewish.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/02/01/ed-koch-dead-nyc-mayor-obituary_n_2597207.html |title=Ed Koch Dead: Mayor Who Became A Symbol Of NYC Dies At 88 (PHOTOS) |work=The Huffington Post |date=February 1, 2013 |accessdate=2013-03-28}}</ref>\n<!-- This LDS rite is controversial and is considered offensive to the Jewish religion by many Jewish people of faith. Discuss on talk page before restoring.-- Pearl was posthumously baptized by the [[LDS Church]] in its practice of [[baptism for the dead]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Keneally|first=Meghan|title=Mormon Church shuts down whistle-blower's access to list of people posthumously baptised|work=[[Daily Mail]]|date=2012-03-08 |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2112157/Mormon-baptism-dead-Church-shuts-access-list-people-posthumously-baptised.html}}</ref>-->\n\n===Movie===\n2007 movie [[A Mighty Heart (film)|A Mighty Heart]] details Pearl's kidnap and murder.<ref name=\"Strupp\">{{cite web |url= http://www.editorandpublisher.com/eandp/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003601970 |title= 'WSJ' Editors Call 'A Mighty Heart' Fair and Accurate |author= Joe Strupp |work= [[Editor & Publisher]] |date= 21 June 2007 |quote= \"It was an accurate portrayal of the [[Wall Street Journal|Journal]] and I think the Journal's people, like [then-foreign editor] John Bussey, who were deeply involved came off well as they should have,\" said former managing editor Paul Steiger, who recalled he saw the movie recently in a private showing for Journal staffers. \"I think Angelina Jolie captured Mariane very, very well.\" Managing Editor [[Marcus Brauchli]], who took over for Steiger and was national editor at the time of Pearl's death, also believed the film was fair. \"I don't feel that the Journal was portrayed badly in the film,\" he said. \"I think we were treated reasonably. Angelina Jolie did a good job of channeling Mariane.\" }}</ref>\n\n===Institutions and awards in Pearl's name===\nShortly after Pearl's death, his parents founded the [[Daniel Pearl Foundation]]. The foundation's mission is to promote cross-cultural understanding through journalism, music, and dialogue. The honorary board of the Daniel Pearl Foundation includes [[Christiane Amanpour]], former US President [[Bill Clinton]], [[Abdul Sattar Edhi]], [[John L. Hennessy]], [[Ted Koppel]], [[Queen Noor of Jordan]], [[Sari Nusseibeh]], [[Mariane Pearl]], [[Itzhak Perlman]], and [[Elie Wiesel]].\n\nThe Daniel Pearl Memorial Lecture at UCLA was established by the foundation in 2002. [[Christopher Hitchens]] delivered a lecture on March 3, 2010. Other lecturers have included [[Anderson Cooper]], [[David Brooks (journalist)|David Brooks]], [[Ted Koppel]], [[Larry King]], [[Jeff Greenfield]], [[Daniel Schorr]], and [[Thomas Friedman]].<ref>Cynthia Lee,[http://newsroom.ucla.edu/portal/ucla/christopher-hitchens-at-ucla-154692.aspx \"Christopher Hitchens decries anti-Semitism in lecture at UCLA\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100402072526/http://newsroom.ucla.edu/portal/ucla/christopher-hitchens-at-ucla-154692.aspx |date=2010-04-02 }}, UCLA newsroom, March 4, 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.international.ucla.edu/burkle/calendar/pearlseries.asp \"The Daniel Pearl Memorial Lecture Series\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080601200548/http://www.international.ucla.edu/burkle/calendar/pearlseries.asp |date=2008-06-01 }}, UCLA</ref> [[Soka University of America]]'s student news magazine, titled ''the Pearl'', is named in honor of Daniel Pearl.\n\nOn May 19, 2010, U.S. President Barack Obama signed the [[Daniel Pearl Freedom of the Press Act]], which protects U.S. journalists around the world. The act is also designed to use tools from the Secretary of State to ensure that freedom of press is upheld in other countries.\n\nIn 2010, ''[[Moment (magazine)|Moment]]'' established [https://www.momentmag.com/the-daniel-pearl-investigative-journalism-initiative/ The Daniel Pearl Investigative Journalism Initiative (DPIJI)] to provide grants and mentors for independent journalists to conduct in-depth reporting on anti-Semitism and other prejudices. The edited stories are published in ''Moment''. The project has already produced two stories that have been nominated for the prestigious Livingston Award\u2014the equivalent of the Pulitzer for journalists under 35.\n\n'''Institutions named after Pearl'''\n*The Sammy Ofer School of Communications at IDC Herzliya introduced the Daniel Pearl International Journalism Institute,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://portal.idc.ac.il/sites/communications_new/en/Communications/research/DPIJI/Pages/Homepage.aspx |title=Daniel Pearl International Journalism Institute |publisher=Portal.idc.ac.il |date=2013-04-17 |accessdate=2013-09-26}}</ref> a new partnership between IDC Herzliya and the Daniel Pearl Foundation. The multimedia newsroom at the School of Communications was named in honor of Daniel Pearl.\n\nThe Charles E. Smith Jewish Day School in Rockville, MD has named their gymnasium after Pearl, with a large block sign reading DANIEL PEARL MEMORIAL GYMNASIUM. The school annually celebrates a Daniel Pearl Day.\n\n'''Awards'''\n*In 2005, ''The Wall Street Journal'', in conjunction with the [[Sciences Po|\u00c9cole de Journalisme de Sciences Po]], gave the first Daniel Pearl Prize to Louis-\u00c9tienne Vigneault-Dubois from Canada, at a ceremony held on June 10 in Paris.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.danielpearl.org/news_and_press/press_releases/journalism_award.html |title=WSJ and Sciences Po Journalism School Award 1st Daniel Pearl Prize to Louis-\u00c9tienne Vigneault-Dubois |publisher=Danielpearl.org |date=2005-06-14 |accessdate=2013-09-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928010747/http://www.danielpearl.org/news_and_press/press_releases/journalism_award.html |archivedate=2013-09-28 }}</ref>\n*In western Massachusetts, with help from the newspapers there for which Pearl worked early in his career (the ''[[North Adams Transcript]]'' and the ''[[Berkshire Eagle]]''), friends of Pearl established the Daniel Pearl Berkshire Scholarship, awarded annually beginning in 2003.\n*Since 2003, Stanford's Department of Communication has awarded a paid summer internship with ''The Wall Street Journal'', known as the \"Daniel Pearl Journalism Internship.\"<ref>http://communication.stanford.edu/internships/pearl/</ref>\n*In 2008 the [[International Consortium of Investigative Journalists]]' bi-annual ICIJ awards were renamed the ''Daniel Pearl Awards for Outstanding International Investigative Reporting''.<ref>[[ICIJ]], [http://www.icij.org/awards DANIEL PEARL AWARDS] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508022548/http://www.icij.org/awards |date=2012-05-08 }}</ref>\n*The Samuel Eells Literary and Educational Foundation annually awards the Brother Daniel Pearl Stanford 85' Award for Literary Excellence to one undergraduate member of the [[Alpha Delta Phi]] Society or Fraternity who has displayed exceptional skill and enthusiasm in fiction, non-fiction, poetry, music and lyrics, photography, or film.\n\n'''Schools named after Pearl'''\n*In May 2007, the Communications Technology Magnet School at [[Birmingham High School]] in Los Angeles was renamed the [[Daniel Pearl Magnet High School]]. In July 2009, it became a stand-alone high school in the Los Angeles Unified School District.\n*In East Brunswick Township, Temple B'nai Shalom renamed their Hebrew School 'The Daniel Pearl Education Center' after Pearl. Additionally, the Synagogue has created a \"Daniel Pearl Education Scholarship\".\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Greater Los Angeles|Israel}}\n* [[2006 Fox journalists kidnapping]]\n* [[History of the Jews in Los Angeles]]\n* [[Islamic terrorism]]\n* People involved in similar kidnappings/murders:<!-- List is alphabetical by family name. -->\n** [[Eugene Armstrong]]\n** [[Nick Berg]]\n** [[Kenneth Bigley]]\n** [[Amjad Hussain Farooqi]]\n** [[James Foley (photojournalist)]]\n** [[Jack Hensley]]\n** [[Margaret Hassan]]\n** [[Paul Marshall Johnson Jr.]]\n** [[Seif Adnan Kanaan]]\n** [[Shosei Koda]]\n** [[Yevgeny Rodionov]]\n** [[Piotr Sta\u0144czak]]\n** [[Kim Sun-il]]\n** [[Austin Tice]]\n\n==References==\n{